# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: connecticut-college
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The **2021 MLS SuperDraft** was the 22nd edition of the SuperDraft conducted by Major League Soccer.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The SuperDraft is held every January prior to the start of the MLS season.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The 2020 SuperDraft was the first held exclusively via conference call and web streaming.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The Draft was once again held virtually, and began on January 21, 2021 at 2:00 p.m.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] Eastern Time, and consisted of three rounds (shortened from four rounds in prior years).
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] Compensatory picks were conveyed to teams that received fourth-round picks via trades.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] Non-playoff clubs receive the next picks in reverse order of prior season finish.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] Teams that made the MLS Cup Playoffs are then ordered by which round of the playoffs they are eliminated.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The winners of the MLS Cup are given the last selection, and the losers the penultimate selection.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The draft was shortened to three rounds, from four rounds as in prior years.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] Compensatory picks were awarded to clubs that had acquired fourth round picks via earlier trades.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] United acquired the 5th and 32nd picks from Atlanta United FC in exchange for the 31st pick and $125,000 in general allocation money.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 6: Chicago Fire → Colorado Rapids → Houston Dynamo**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] December 13, 2020: Colorado Rapids acquired a first-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Chicago Fire FC in exchange for $125,000 in general allocation money.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The pick was Chicago's natural selection.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] January 21, 2021: Colorado Rapids acquired a first-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Houston Dynamo in exchange for $200,000 in general allocation money and the 6th overall draft pick.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The pick was Houston's natural selection.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 8: LA Galaxy → Portland Timbers → Orlando City**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] January 12, 2021: Portland Timbers acquired a first-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from LA Galaxy in exchange for Jorge Villafaña and swapping first-round selections.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The pick was Galaxy's natural selection.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] Portland subsequently traded Galaxy's pick on January 21, 2021, to Orlando City in exchange for $100,000 general allocation money.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] December 15, 2020: Austin FC acquired a first-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from CF Montréal and $225,000 in general allocation money in exchange for Kamal Miller.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] January 13, 2021: FC Dallas acquired a first-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Colorado Rapids in exchange for Michael Barrios and swapping first-round selections.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The pick was Colorado's natural selection.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 8: LA Galaxy → Portland Timbers → Orlando City.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 17: New York City FC → Minnesota United**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] January 21, 2021: Minnesota United acquired the 17th selection from New York City FC in exchange for $50,000 in general allocation money.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] Minnesota United acquired the 18th selection from Toronto FC in exchange for the 25th selection and $50,000 in general allocation money.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 19: Philadelphia Union → Orlando City**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] July 17, 2020: Orlando City SC acquired a first-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft in exchange for the homegrown player rights to Nathan Harriel.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The traded pick was Philadelphia's natural selection.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 21: FC Dallas → Colorado Rapids → Austin FC**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] Austin FC subsequently acquired the FC Dallas selection (21st overall) from Colorado Rapids in exchange for $50,000 in general allocation money.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 23: Sporting Kansas City → Vancouver Whitecaps FC**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] December 14, 2018: Vancouver Whitecaps FC acquired a first-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft in exchange for Erik Hurtado.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The traded picks were Kansas City's natural selections.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 26: Seattle Sounders FC → Inter Miami**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] September 28, 2020: Inter Miami CF acquired a first-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft in exchange for Román Torres.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 36: Vancouver Whitecaps FC → Nashville SC**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] January 21, 2021: Nashville SC traded a 2021 international spot and its second-round selection (46th overall) in the 2021 MLS SuperDraft, to Vancouver Whitecaps FC for $175,000 in general allocation money and Vancouver's second-round selection (36th overall).
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] October 1, 2020: Minnesota United FC acquired a second-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft and $600,000 in general allocation money from CF Montréal in exchange for forward Mason Toye.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 46: Philadelphia Union → Nashville SC → Vancouver Whitecaps FC**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] January 19, 2021: Nashville SC acquired second- and third-round selections in the 2021 SuperDraft and a first-round selection in the 2022 SuperDraft in exchange for up to $225,000 of general allocation money.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 46: Vancouver Whitecaps FC → Nashville SC**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] November 12, 2019: Chicago Fire FC acquired a second-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft, $50,000 in general allocation money, and $50,000 in targeted allocation money from Nashville SC in exchange for midfielder Dax McCarty.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] February 12, 2020: Columbus Crew acquired a second-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Minnesota United FC in exchange for the MLS rights to Aaron Schoenfeld.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 53: Seattle Sounders FC → Vancouver Whitecaps FC**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] August 22, 2019: Vancouver Whitecaps FC acquired a second-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Seattle Sounders FC in exchange for an international roster spot for the remainder of the 2019 MLS season.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] August 17, 2020: FC Cincinnati acquired a second-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Columbus Crew in exchange for Fatai Alashe.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 63: Vancouver Whitecaps FC → CF Montréal**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] September 28, 2020: CF Montréal acquired a third-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Vancouver Whitecaps FC in exchange for goalkeeper Evan Bush.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] December 28, 2019: Toronto FC acquired a third-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Inter Miami CF in exchange for the MLS rights to forward Juan Agudelo.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 73: Philadelphia Union → Nashville SC**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 46: Philadelphia Union → Nashville SC → Vancouver Whitecaps.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] February 27, 2020: FC Dallas acquired a third-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Orlando City SC.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] January 21, 2020: FC Dallas acquired a third-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Minnesota United FC in exchange for midfielder Jacori Hayes.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 81: Columbus Crew → Inter Miami → New York Red Bulls**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] August 14, 2020: Inter Miami CF acquired a third-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Columbus Crew SC in exchange for defender Grant Lillard.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] On December 23, 2020, New York Red Bulls acquired this pick in exchange for Patrick Seagrist.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 83: Vancouver Whitecaps FC → Inter Miami**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] January 29, 2020: Inter Miami CF acquired a fourth-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Vancouver Whitecaps FC in exchange for goalkeeper Bryan Meredith.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] The traded pick was Vancouver's natural selection.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] February 19, 2018: Real Salt Lake acquired a fourth-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft from Colorado Rapids in exchange for the MLS rights to midfielder Enzo Martínez.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] 85: New England Revolution → Inter Miami**.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] September 8, 2020: New England Revolution reacquired midfielder Lee Nguyen from Inter Miami CF in exchange for a fourth-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft and up to $50,000 in general allocation money.
[src:connecticut-college/2021-mls-superdraft] September 18, 2020: Minnesota United FC acquired goalkeeper Adrian Zendejas in exchange for a fourth-round selection in the 2021 SuperDraft and up to $100,000 in general allocation money if he meets certain performance-based metrics for Minnesota.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] An **academic honor code** or honor system in the United States is a set of rules or ethical principles governing an academic community based on ideals that define what constitutes honorable behaviour within that community.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] The use of an honor code depends on the notion that people (at least within the community) can be trusted to act honorably.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] One of the first such codes was created at the College of William & Mary in the early 18th Century.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] Presently, some of the most notable and most stringent honor codes exist at the Federal Service Academies and Senior Military Colleges.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] The military academy honor codes not only govern the cadets and midshipmen's lives at the academies but also are deemed essential to the development of military officers who are worthy of the public trust.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] As such, the codes are not limited merely to academic situations or to conduct on campus; cadets and midshipmen are expected to live by the codes' ethical standards at all times.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] The codes are as old as the academies themselves and simply state that cadets and midshipmen do not lie, cheat or steal, nor tolerate those who do.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] A single-sanction Honor Code, in which any offense results in expulsion regardless of severity, exists at Virginia Military Institute, which features a "drum out" ceremony which is still carried out upon a cadet's dismissal.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] Outside of the military, Washington and Lee University has a single sanction code.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] At three of the service academies and at Virginia Military Institute, anyone who learns of an honor code violation is required to report it.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] Failure to do so is considered "toleration," which itself violates the code.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] The Honor Concept of the Brigade of Midshipmen at the United States Naval Academy allows the observer of an honor violation to confront the accused without formally reporting.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] It was found that it was more constructive at developing the honor of midshipmen.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] A non-toleration clause, on the other hand, is believed to make enemies of classmates.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] Additionally, it is thought that one's true honor, if other than utmost, was not able to be formally remediated when hidden from public view.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] Under the academies' honor codes, violators can face severe punishment, up to being forwarded for expulsion by the Secretary of the Army, Navy, or Air Force.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] Stringent honor codes, however, are not limited to military institutions.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] Like the Naval Academy, however, those who witness a violation are encouraged to confront the violator and convince them to turn themselves in before resorting to reporting the violation.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] Another school with a very strict honor code is Brigham Young University.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] The university not only mandates honest behavior but also incorporates various aspects of Mormon religious law: drinking, smoking, drug use, premarital sex and same-sex relationships are all banned.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] Also, the code includes standards for dress and grooming.
[src:connecticut-college/academic-honor-code] Men must be clean-shaven, and men and women cannot wear short shorts or other revealing clothing.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The **Academy Awards**, more commonly known as the **Oscars**, are awards based on artistic and technical merit in film.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] They are presented annually by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS) in the United States in recognition of excellence in cinematic achievements, as assessed by the Academy's voting membership.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Oscars are widely considered to be the most prestigious awards in the American film industry, predominantly centered around films produced in Hollywood.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The major award categories, known as the **Academy Awards of Merit**, are presented during a live televised Hollywood ceremony in February or March.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] It is the longest running worldwide entertainment awards ceremony.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The 1st Academy Awards were held in 1929.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The second ceremony, in 1930, was the first to be broadcast by radio, and the 1953 ceremony was the first to be televised.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] It is the oldest of the four major annual American entertainment awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Its counterparts — the Emmy Awards for television, the Tony Awards for Broadway theatre, and the Grammy Awards for music — are modeled after the Academy Awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Oscar statuette depicts a knight, rendered in the Art Deco style.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The first Academy Awards presentation was held on May 16, 1929 at a private dinner function at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel, with an audience of about 270 people.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The post-awards party was held at the Mayfair Hotel.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The cost of guest tickets for that night's ceremony was $5 (equivalent to $94 in 2025).
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Fifteen statuettes were awarded, honoring artists, directors, and other participants in the film-making industry of the time, for their works during the 1927–28 period.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For this first ceremony, winners were announced to the media three months earlier.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For the second ceremony in 1930, and the rest of the first decade, the results were given to newspapers for publication at 11:00 pm on the night of the awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 1940, the *Los Angeles Times* announced the winners before the ceremony began.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] As a result, in 1941 the Academy started using a sealed envelope to reveal the names of the winners.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The term "Oscar" is a registered trademark of the AMPAS.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Historically, the Oscars had been the prime example of glamor in the United States; however, a movement away from both network television and award shows has led to the shift of the focus of glamor from the Oscars to the Met Gala.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Oscars have suffered declining network television ratings and will be moving to YouTube in 2029.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The first Best Actor awarded was Emil Jannings, for his performances in *The Last Command* and *The Way of All Flesh*.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] As he had to return to Europe before the ceremony, the Academy agreed to give him the prize early, making him the first Academy Award recipient.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For the first Awards, winners were recognized for multiple films during the qualifying period; Jannings received the award for two films in which he starred, and Janet Gaynor won the first Best Actress award for performances in three films.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Beginning with the second ceremony, performers received separate nominations for individual films; no performer has received multiple nominations in the same category since the 3rd Academy Awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For the first five ceremonies, the eligibility period ran from August 1 to July 31.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Best Foreign Language Film, now known as Best International Feature Film, was introduced at the 20th Academy Awards as a special award, and became a competitive category at the 29th Academy Awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The 74th Academy Awards, held in 2002, presented the first Academy Award for Best Animated Feature, won by *Shrek*.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Since 1973, all Academy Awards ceremonies, except for 2021, have ended with the Academy Award for Best Picture.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Traditionally, the winners of the acting categories will present an award at the following year's ceremony.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The previous year's winners for Best Actor and Best Supporting Actor present the awards for Best Actress and Best Supporting Actress, respectively, and vice versa.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2009, this model was replaced by each acting award being introduced by five previous winners, each of whom introduces one of the nominated performances, referred to as the "Fab 5" presenters format.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Fab 5 model returned in 2024 after a 15-year hiatus.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] On February 9, 2020, *Parasite* became the first foreign-language film to win Best Picture at the 92nd Academy Awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The 93rd Academy Awards ceremony, honoring the best films of 2020 and early 2021, was held on April 25, 2021, after it was postponed from its original February 28, 2021, schedule due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on cinema.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] As with the two previous ceremonies, there was no host.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] It took place at the Dolby Theatre in Los Angeles, California for the 19th consecutive year, with satellite locations at Union Station also in Los Angeles.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Because of the virus impact on films and TV industries, Academy president David Rubin and CEO Dawn Hudson announced that for the 2021 Oscar Ceremony, streaming films with a previously planned theatrical release were eligible.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The theatrical requirement was reinstated starting with the 95th Academy Awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Oscar statuette, officially the Academy Award of Merit, is given to winners of each year's awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Made of gold-plated bronze on a black metal base, it is 13.5 in (34.3 cm) tall, weighs 8.5 lb (3.9 kg) and depicts a knight rendered in Art Deco style holding a sword standing on a reel of film with five spokes.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The five spokes represent the original branches of the Academy: Actors, Writers, Directors, Producers, and Technicians.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Sculptor George Stanley, who also did the Muse Fountain at the Hollywood Bowl, sculpted Cedric Gibbons' design.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The statuettes presented at the initial ceremonies were gold-plated solid bronze.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Within a few years, the bronze was abandoned in favor of Britannia metal, a pewter-like alloy that is then plated in copper, nickel silver, and finally, 24-karat gold.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Due to a metal shortage during World War II, Oscars were made of painted plaster for three years.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Following the war, the Academy invited recipients to redeem the plaster figures for gold-plated metal ones.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The only addition to the Oscar since it was created is a minor streamlining of the base.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The original Oscar mold was cast in 1928 at the C.W.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Shumway & Sons Foundry in Batavia, Illinois, which also contributed to casting the molds for the Vince Lombardi Trophy and Emmy Award statuettes.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] From 1972 to 1986, the Oscar statues were cast at the Dodge Trophy Company in Crystal Lake, Illinois.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] From 1987 to 2015, approximately 50 Oscars in a tin alloy with gold plating were made each year in Chicago by Illinois manufacturer R.S.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] It would take between three and four weeks to manufacture 50 statuettes.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2016, the Academy returned to bronze as the core metal of the statuettes, handing manufacturing duties to Walden, New York-based Polich Tallix Fine Art Foundry, now owned and operated by UAP Urban Art Projects.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] While based on a digital scan of an original 1929 Oscar, the statuettes retain their modern-era dimensions and black pedestal.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Cast in liquid bronze from 3D-printed ceramic molds and polished, they are then electroplated in 24-karat gold by Brooklyn, New York-based Epner Technology.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The time required to produce 50 such statuettes is roughly three months.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Owens is expected to continue producing other awards for the Academy, and service existing Oscars that need replating.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The origin of the nickname of the trophy has been disputed, as multiple people have taken credit for naming the trophy "Oscar".
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Margaret Herrick, librarian and president of the Academy, may have said she named it after her supposed uncle Oscar in 1931.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The only corroboration was a 1938 clipping from the *Los Angeles Examiner*, in which Herrick told a story of her and her husband joking with each other using the phrase, "How's your uncle Oscar".
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Bette Davis, in her 1962 autobiography, claimed she named it in 1936 after her first husband, Harmon Oscar Nelson, of whom the statue's rear end reminded her.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] But the term had been in use at least two years before.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] But in the newspaper clipping that Skolsky referred to, he wrote that "these statues are called 'Oscars'", meaning that the name was already in use.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2021, Brazilian researcher Waldemar Dalenogare Neto contradicted Skolsky's claim to have used the term first, finding the probable first public mention of the name "Oscar" in journalist Relman Morin's "Cinematters" column in the *Los Angeles Evening Record* on December 5, 1933.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Since the awards did not take place that year, he said: "What's happened to the annual Academy banquet?
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Bruce Davis, a former executive director of the Academy, credited Eleanore Lilleberg, a secretary at the Academy when the award was first introduced, for the nickname.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] She had overseen the pre-ceremony handling of the awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Davis credits Lilleberg because he found in an autobiography of Einar Lilleberg, Eleanore's brother, that Einar had referenced a Norwegian army veteran named Oscar whom the two knew in Chicago, whom Einar described as having always "stood straight and tall".
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] He asserts credit "should almost certainly belong to" Lilleberg.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] To prevent information identifying the Oscar winners from leaking ahead of the ceremony, Oscar statuettes presented at the ceremony have blank baseplates.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Until 2010, winners returned their statuettes to the Academy and had to wait several weeks to have their names inscribed on their respective Oscars.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Since 2010, winners have had the option of having engraved nameplates applied to their statuettes at an inscription-processing station at the Governor's Ball, a party held immediately after the Oscar ceremony.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Owens company has engraved nameplates made before the ceremony, bearing the name of every potential winner.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The nameplates for the non-winning nominees are later recycled.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Before 1950, Oscar statuettes were, and remain, the property of the recipient.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Since then the statuettes have been legally encumbered by the requirement that the statuette be first offered for sale back to the Academy for $1.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] If a winner refuses to agree to this stipulation, then the Academy keeps the statuette.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Academy Awards predating this agreement have been sold in public auctions and private deals for six-figure sums.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 1989, Michael Todd's grandson tried to sell Todd's Best Picture Oscar for his 1956 production of *Around the World in 80 Days* to a movie prop collector.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy earned enforcement of its statuette contract by gaining a permanent injunction against the sale.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 1992, Harold Russell consigned his 1946 Oscar for Best Supporting Actor for *The Best Years of Our Lives* to auction to raise money for his wife's medical expenses.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Though his decision caused controversy, the first Oscar ever to be sold passed to a private collector on August 6, 1992, for $60,500 (equivalent to $138,804 in 2025).
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Russell defended his action, saying, "I don't know why anybody would be critical.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] My wife's health is much more important than sentimental reasons.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The movie will be here, even if Oscar isn't".
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In December 2011, Orson Welles' 1941 Oscar for *Citizen Kane* (Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay) was put up for auction, after his heirs won a 2004 court decision contending that Welles did not sign any agreement to return the statue to the Academy.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Some buyers have subsequently returned the statuettes to the Academy, which keeps them in its treasury.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy also awards Nicholl Fellowships in Screenwriting.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] From 2004 to 2020, the Academy Award nomination results were announced to the public in mid-January.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Prior to that, the results were announced in early February.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2021, the nominees were announced in March.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2022, the nominees were announced in early February for the first time since 2003.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS), a professional honorary organization, is composed of 9,905 voting members as of 2024.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Academy membership is divided into different branches, with each representing a different discipline in film production.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] As of 2024, actors constitute the largest bloc, numbering 1,258 (12.7% of the voting body).
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Votes have been certified by the auditing firm PricewaterhouseCoopers, and its predecessor Price Waterhouse, since the 7th Academy Awards in 1935.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In May 2011, the Academy sent a letter advising its then-6,000 or so voting members that an online system for Oscar voting would be implemented in 2013, replacing mailed paper ballots.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] All AMPAS members must be invited to join by the Board of Governors, on behalf of Academy Branch Executive Committees.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Membership eligibility may be achieved by a competitive nomination, or an existing member may submit a name, based on other significant contributions to the field of motion pictures.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] New membership proposals are considered annually.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy does not publicly disclose its membership, although as recently as 2007 press releases have announced the names of those who have been invited to join.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2012, the results of a study conducted by the *Los Angeles Times* were published describing the demographic breakdown of approximately 88% of AMPAS' voting membership.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Of the 5,100+ active voters confirmed, 94% were Caucasian, 77% were male, and 54% were found to be over the age of 60.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Thirty-three percent of voting members are former nominees (14%) and winners (19%).
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2016, the Academy launched an initiative to expand its membership and increase diversity.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2024, voting membership stood at 9,905.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2025, a newly announced procedure required Academy members to view all nominated films within a category to be eligible to cast a vote in the final round of that category.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The verification process will be done through the Academy's members-only streaming platform and submitting a form for films viewed at in-person events such as at festivals, screenings or private events.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The film must be shown at least three times on each day of its qualifying run, with at least one of the daily showings starting between 6 pm and 10 pm local time.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For example, the 2009 Best Picture winner, *The Hurt Locker*, was originally first released in 2008, but did not qualify for the 2008 awards, as it did not play its Oscar-qualifying run in Los Angeles until mid-2009, thus qualifying for the 2009 awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Foreign films must include English subtitles.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Each country can submit only one film for consideration in the International Feature Film category per year.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Rule 2 states that a film must be feature-length, defined as a minimum of 40 minutes, except for short-subject awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] It must exist either on a 35 mm or 70 mm film print, or in 24 frame/s or 48 frame/s progressive scan digital cinema format, with a minimum projector resolution of 2,048 by 1,080 pixels.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Since the 90th Academy Awards, presented in 2018, multi-part and limited series have been ineligible for the Best Documentary Feature award.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] This followed the win of *O.J.: Made in America*, an eight-hour presentation that was screened in a limited release before being broadcast in five parts on ABC and ESPN, in that category in 2017.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy's announcement of the new rule made no direct mention of that film.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Best International Feature Film award does not require a U.S. release.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] It requires the film to be submitted as its country's official selection.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The qualifying theatrical runs must meet the same requirements as those for non-documentary films regarding numbers and times of screenings.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] A film must have been reviewed by a critic from *The New York Times*, *Time Out New York*, the *Los Angeles Times*, or *LA Weekly*.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Producers must submit an Official Screen Credits online form before the deadline.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] If it is not submitted by the defined deadline, the film will be ineligible for Academy Awards in any year.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The form includes the production credits for all related categories.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Awards in short film categories (Best Documentary Short Subject, Best Animated Short Film, and Best Live Action Short Film) have different eligibility rules from most other competitive awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] First, the qualifying period for release does not coincide with a calendar year, instead covering one year starting on October 1, and ending on September 30 of the calendar year before the ceremony.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Second, there are multiple methods of qualification.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The main method is a week-long theatrical release in *either* New York City *or* Los Angeles County during the eligibility period.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Films can also qualify by winning specified awards at one of several competitive film festivals designated by the Academy, also without regard to prior public distribution.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] A film that is selected as a gold, silver, or bronze medal winner in an appropriate category of the immediately previous Student Academy Awards is also eligible (Documentary category for that award, and Animation, Narrative, Alternative, or International for the other awards).
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The requirements for the qualifying theatrical run are also different from those for other awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For the Documentary award, the screening must start between noon and 10 pm local time.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For other awards, no specific start time is required, but the film must appear in regular theater listings with dates and screening times.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In late December, ballots and lists of eligible films are sent to the membership.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For most categories, members from each of the branches vote to determine the nominees only in their respective categories, i.e. only directors vote for directors, writers for writers, actors for actors, etc.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In the special case of Best Picture, all voting members are eligible to select the nominees.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] A number of branches are only eligible to vote in Best Picture during nomination voting; this includes a producers' branch, as Best Picture is awarded to a film's producer(s), and other branches which have no corresponding award.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In all major categories, a variant of the single transferable vote is used, with each member casting a ballot with up to five nominees (ten for Best Picture) ranked preferentially.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In certain categories, including International Feature Film, Documentary and Animated Feature, nominees are selected by special screening committees made up of members from all branches.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In most categories, the winner is selected from among the nominees by plurality voting of all members.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Since 2009, the Best Picture winner has been chosen by instant-runoff voting.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Since 2013, re-weighted range voting has been used to select the nominees for the Best Visual Effects.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Film companies will spend as much as several million dollars on marketing to awards voters for a film in the running for Best Picture, in attempts to improve chances of receiving Oscars and other film awards conferred in Oscar season.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy enforces rules to limit overt campaigning by its members to try to eliminate excesses and prevent the process from becoming undignified.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] It has an awards czar on staff who advises members on allowed practices and levies penalties on offenders.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For example, a producer of the 2009 Best Picture nominee *The Hurt Locker* was disqualified as a producer in the category when he contacted associates urging them to vote for his film and not another that was seen as the front-runner.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For the 99th Academy Awards (2027) and thereafter, AMPAS announced on May 1, 2026, its planned rules of eligibility.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Actors and scripts generated by artificial intelligence (AI) will be excluded from acting and screenwriting categories, but human actors rendered by AI will be reviewed at discretion.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Another rule change will expand eligibility of international films by allowing films that won eligible qualifying awards at film festivals, like the Palme d'Or (Cannes), the Golden Lion (Venice), and the Platform Prize (Toronto).
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Another new rule will allow an actor to be nominated more than once in a same acting category of the year.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Another rule change will clarify eligibility of the Best Original Song category: to be eligible, a first song played as the "first music cue" of the end credits must be heard in at least the film's last fifteen seconds until the end credits start.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy Screening Room or Academy Digital Screening Room is a secure streaming platform which allows voting members of the Academy to view all eligible films in one place.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] It was introduced in 2019, for the 2020 Oscars.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] DVD screeners and Academy in-person screenings were still provided.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For films to be included on the platform, the North American distributor must pay $12,500, including a watermarking fee, and a digital copy of the film to be prepared for streaming by the Academy.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The platform can be accessed via Apple TV and Roku players.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The watermarking process involved several video security firms, creating a forensic watermark and restricting the ability to take screenshots or screen recordings.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2021, for the 2022 Oscars, the Academy banned all physical screeners and in-person screenings, restricting official membership viewing to the Academy Screening Room.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Films eligible in the Documentary and International categories were made available in different sections of the platform.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Distributors can also pay an extra fee to add video featurettes to promote their films on the platform.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The in-person screenings were cancelled because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Eligible films do not have to be added to the platform, but the Academy advertises them to voting members when they are.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The major awards are presented at a live televised ceremony, commonly in late February or early March following the relevant calendar year, and six weeks after the announcement of the nominees.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] It is the culmination of the film awards season, which usually begins during November or December of the previous year.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] This is an elaborate extravaganza, with the invited guests walking up the red carpet in the creations of the most prominent fashion designers of the day.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Black tie dress is the most common outfit for men.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Fashion may dictate not wearing a bow tie, and musical performers are sometimes not required to adhere to this.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The artists who recorded the nominees for Best Original Song quite often perform those songs live at the awards ceremony, and the fact that they are performing is often used to promote the television broadcast.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy Awards is the world's longest-running awards show televised live from the United States to all time zones in North America and worldwide, and gathers millions of viewers elsewhere throughout the world.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Oscars were first televised in 1953 by NBC, which continued to broadcast the event until 1960, when ABC took over, televising the festivities, including the first color broadcast of the event in 1966, to 1970.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] NBC regained the rights for five years (1971–75), then ABC resumed broadcast duties in 1976 and its current contract with the Academy runs through 2028, after which the ceremony will be broadcast exclusively on YouTube starting with 2029's ceremony.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy has produced condensed versions of the ceremony for broadcast in international markets, especially those outside of the Americas, in more desirable local timeslots.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The ceremony was broadcast live internationally for the first time via satellite since 1970, but only two South American countries, Chile and Brazil, purchased the rights to air the broadcast.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] By that time, the television rights to the Academy Awards had been sold in 50 countries.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 1980, the rights were sold to 60 countries, and by 1984, the television rights to the Academy Awards were licensed in 76 countries.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2004, the ceremonies were moved up from late March/early April to late February, to help disrupt and shorten the intense lobbying and ad campaigns associated with Oscar season in the film industry.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Another reason was because of the growing television ratings success coinciding with the NCAA division I men's basketball tournament, which would cut into the Academy Awards audience.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 1976 and 1977, ABC's regained Oscars were moved from Tuesday to Monday and went directly opposite the national championship game on NBC.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The earlier date is also to the advantage of ABC, as it now usually occurs during the highly profitable and important February sweeps period.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Some years, the ceremony is moved into the first Sunday of March to avoid a clash with the Winter Olympics.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Another reason for the move to late February and early March is to avoid the awards ceremony occurring so close to the religious holidays of Passover and Easter, which for decades had been a grievance from members and the general public.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Advertising is somewhat restricted, as traditionally no film studios or competitors of official Academy Award sponsors may advertise during the telecast.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] As of 2020, the production of the Academy Awards telecast held the distinction of winning one the highest number of Emmys in history, with 54 wins and 280 nominations overall.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] After many years of being held on Mondays at 6:00 p.m.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Eastern, since the 1999 ceremony, it was moved to Sundays at 5:30 p.m.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The reasons given for the move were that more viewers would tune in on Sundays, that Los Angeles rush-hour traffic jams could be avoided, and an earlier start time would prevent the ceremony from going late into the night in the East.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] For many years the film industry opposed a Sunday broadcast because it would cut into the weekend box office.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2010, the Academy contemplated moving the ceremony even further back into January, citing television viewers' fatigue with the film industry's long awards season.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] However, such an accelerated schedule would dramatically decrease the voting period for its members, to the point where some voters would only have time to view the contending films streamed on their computers, as opposed to traditionally receiving the films and ballots in the mail.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Additionally, a January ceremony on Sunday would clash with National Football League (NFL) playoff games.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2018, the Academy announced that the ceremony would be moved from late February to mid-February beginning with the 92nd Academy Awards in 2020.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2024, the ceremony was moved to an even earlier start time of 4:00 p.m.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] ET, in an effort to improve East Coast viewership by having it conclude within primetime hours.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The change also gave the ability for ABC to air a half-hour of primetime programming as a lead-out program at 7:30 p.m.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] ET, after having sometimes done so in the late-night block following late local newscasts.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Originally scheduled for April 8, 1968, the 40th Academy Awards ceremony was postponed for two days, because of the assassination of Dr.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] On March 30, 1981, the 53rd Academy Awards was postponed for one day, after the attempted assassination of President Ronald Reagan and others in Washington, D.C.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 1993, an *In Memoriam* segment was introduced, honoring those who had made a significant contribution to cinema who had died in the preceding 12 months, a selection compiled by a small committee of Academy members.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] This segment has drawn criticism over the years for the omission of some names.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Criticism was also levied for many years regarding another aspect, with the segment having a "popularity contest" feel as the audience varied their applause to those who had died by the subject's cultural impact.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The applause has since been muted during the telecast, and the audience is discouraged from clapping during the segment and giving silent reflection instead.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] This segment was later followed by a commercial break.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In terms of broadcast length, the ceremony generally averages three and a half hours.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The first Oscars, in 1929, lasted 15 minutes.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] At the other end of the spectrum, the 2002 ceremony lasted four hours and twenty-three minutes.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2010, the organizers of the Academy Awards announced winners' acceptance speeches must not run past 45 seconds.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] This, according to organizer Bill Mechanic, was to ensure the elimination of what he termed "the single most hated thing on the show"—overly long and embarrassing displays of emotion.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2016, in a further effort to streamline speeches, winners' dedications were displayed on an on-screen ticker.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] During the 2018 ceremony, host Jimmy Kimmel acknowledged how long the ceremony had become, by announcing that he would give a brand-new jet ski to whoever gave the shortest speech of the night, a reward won by Mark Bridges when accepting his Best Costume Design award for *Phantom Thread*.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Although still dominant in ratings, the viewership of the Academy Awards has steadily dropped.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The 88th Academy Awards were the lowest-rated in the past eight years (although with increases in male and 18–49 viewership), while the show itself also faced mixed reception.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Following the show, *Variety* reported that ABC was, in negotiating an extension to its contract to broadcast the Oscars, seeking to have more creative control over the broadcast itself.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Currently and nominally, AMPAS is responsible for most aspects of the telecast, including the choice of production staff and hosting, although ABC is allowed to have some input on their decisions.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In August 2016, AMPAS extended its contract with ABC to 2028: the contract neither contains any notable changes nor gives ABC any further creative control over the telecast.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] On December 17, 2025, the Academy announced that YouTube had acquired the rights to the Academy Awards beginning with the 101st ceremony in 2029, replacing ABC under a contract that will last through 2033.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] YouTube will serve as the exclusive worldwide broadcaster of the ceremony, while the Oscars' YouTube channel will also feature other AMPAS-produced ancillary content and events (including ceremonies, interviews, and other digital content).
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy will also partner with the Google Arts & Culture program to help digitize portions of the Academy Museum of Motion Pictures and the organization's collection.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Historically, the telecast's viewership is higher when box-office hits are favored to win the Best Picture award.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] More than 57.25 million viewers tuned to the telecast for the 70th Academy Awards in 1998, the year of *Titanic*, which generated a box office haul during its initial 1997–98 run of $600.8 million in the US, a box-office record that would remain unsurpassed for years.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The 76th Academy Awards ceremony, in which *The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King* (pre-telecast box office earnings of $368 million) received 11 Awards, including Best Picture, drew 43.56 million viewers.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The most-watched ceremony based on Nielsen ratings to date, was the 42nd Academy Awards (Best Picture *Midnight Cowboy*), which drew a 43.4% household rating on April 7, 1970.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Hoping to reinvigorate the pre-show and ratings, the 2023 Oscars organizers hired members of the Met Gala creative team.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] By contrast, ceremonies honoring films that have not performed well at the box office tend to show weaker ratings, despite how much critical acclaim those films have received.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The 78th Academy Awards, which awarded a low-budget independent film (*Crash* with a pre-Oscar gross of $53.4 million) generated an audience of 38.64 million with a household rating of 22.91%.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2008, the 80th Academy Awards telecast was watched by 31.76 million viewers on average with an 18.66% household rating, the lowest-rated and least-watched ceremony at the time, in spite of celebrating 80 years of the Academy Awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Best Picture winner of that particular ceremony was another independent film (this time, the Coen brothers's *No Country for Old Men*).
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Whereas the 92nd Academy Awards drew an average of 23.6 million viewers, the 93rd Academy Awards drew an even lower viewership of 10.4 million, the lowest viewership recorded by Nielsen since it started recording audience totals in 1974.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The 94th and 95th editions drew 16.6 and 18.7 million viewers, respectively, still below the audience of the 92nd edition.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Academy Film Archive holds copies of every Academy Awards ceremony since the 1949 Oscars, as well as material on many prior ceremonies, along with ancillary material related to more recent shows.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Copies are held in a variety of film, video and digital formats.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 1929, the first Academy Awards were presented at a banquet dinner at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] From 1930 to 1943, the ceremony alternated between two venues: the Ambassador Hotel on Wilshire Boulevard and the Biltmore Hotel in downtown Los Angeles.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Grauman's Chinese Theatre in Hollywood then hosted the awards from 1944 to 1946, followed by the Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles from 1947 to 1948.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The 21st Academy Awards in 1949 were held at the Academy Award Theatre at what had been the Academy's headquarters on Melrose Avenue in Hollywood.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] From 1950 to 1960, the awards were presented at Hollywood's Pantages Theatre.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] With the advent of television, the awards from 1953 to 1957 took place simultaneously in Hollywood and New York, first at the NBC International Theatre (1953) and the Center Theater (1954), then at the NBC Century Theatre, after which the ceremony took place solely in Los Angeles.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 1961, the Oscars moved to the Santa Monica Civic Auditorium in Santa Monica, California.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 1969, the Academy moved the ceremonies back to Downtown Los Angeles, to the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion at the Los Angeles County Music Center.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the ceremony returned to the Shrine Auditorium.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In 2002, Hollywood's Dolby Theatre, previously known as the Kodak Theatre, became the presentation's current venue.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In March 2026, it was announced that the ceremony would relocate to the Peacock Theater beginning in 2029, under a ten-year deal with the venue.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In the first year of the awards, the Best Directing award was split into two categories, Drama and Comedy.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] At times, the Best Original Score award has also been split into separate categories, Drama and Comedy/Musical.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] From the 1930s to the 1960s, the Art Direction (now Production Design), Cinematography, and Costume Design awards were split into two categories (black-and-white films and color films).
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Prior to 2012, the Production Design award was called Art Direction, while the Makeup and Hairstyling award was called Makeup.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Prior to 2020, the International Feature Film award was called Foreign Language Film.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In August 2018, the Academy announced that several categories would not be televised live, but recorded during commercial breaks and aired later in the ceremony.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] Following dissent from Academy members, they announced that they would air all 24 categories live.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] This followed several proposals, among them, the introduction of a Popular Film category, that the Academy had announced but did not implement.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In February 2024, the Academy announced it would introduce an award for Achievement in Casting from the 98th ceremony in 2026, having rejected the category in 1999.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] In April 2025, it announced that Best Stunt Design would be introduced from the 100th ceremony in 2028, having rejected the proposal for a Best Stunt Coordination award every year from 1991 to 2012.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] The Special Academy Awards are voted on by special committees, rather than by the Academy membership as a whole.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p01] They are not always presented on an annual basis.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Due to the positive exposure and prestige of the Academy Awards, many studios spend around 25 million dollars and hire publicists specifically to promote their films during what is typically called the "Oscar season".
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] This has generated accusations of the Academy Awards being influenced more by marketing and lobbying than by quality.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] William Friedkin, an Academy Award-winning film director and former producer of the ceremony, expressed this sentiment at a conference in New York in 2009, describing it as "the greatest promotion scheme that any industry ever devised for itself".
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] A recent technique that has been claimed to be used during the Oscar season is the whisper campaign.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] These campaigns are intended to spread negative perceptions of other films nominated and are believed to be perpetrated by those who were involved in creating the film.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Examples of whisper campaigns include the allegations against *Zero Dark Thirty* suggesting that it justifies torture and the claim that *Lincoln* distorts history.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] This technique was widely used by former producer Harvey Weinstein and his company Miramax, with the campaign strategy gaining further attention after Miramax's *Shakespeare in Love* defeated rival film *Saving Private Ryan* for Best Picture.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The Oscars have been infamously known for selecting specific genres of films to be awarded.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The term "Oscar bait" was coined to describe such films.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] This has led, at times, to more specific criticisms that the Academy is disconnected from the audience, e.g., by favoring "Oscar bait" over audience favorites or favoring historical melodramas over critically acclaimed films that depict current life issues.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Despite the success of *The Dark Knight* and *WALL-E*, these films did not receive a Best Picture nomination at the 81st Academy Awards.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] These decisions received substantial criticism and were described as "snubs" by many publications.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The backlash to the decision was such that, for the 82nd Academy Awards in 2010, the Academy increased the limit for Best Picture nominees from five to ten.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The Academy Awards have long received criticism over their lack of diversity among the nominees.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] This criticism is based on the statistics from every Academy Awards since 1929, which show that only 6.4% of Academy Award nominees have been non-white and since 1991, 11.2% of nominees have been non-white, with the rate of winners being even more polarizing.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] For a variety of reasons, including marketability and historical bans on interracial couples, a number of high-profile Oscars have been given to yellowface portrayals, as well as performances of Asian characters rewritten for white characters.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] It took until 2023 for an Asian woman to win an Academy Award for Best Actress, when Michelle Yeoh received the award for her performance in *Everything Everywhere All at Once*.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The 88th awards ceremony became the target of a boycott, popularized on social media with the hashtag #OscarsSoWhite, based on activists' perception that its all-white acting nominee list reflected bias.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] In response, the Academy initiated "historic" changes in membership by 2020.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Some media critics claim the Academy's efforts to address its purported racial, gender and national biases are merely distractions.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] By contrast, the Golden Globe Awards already have multiple winners of Asian descent in leading actress categories.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Some question whether the Academy's definition of "merit" is just or empowering for non-Americans.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The Academy's Representation and Inclusion Standards have been criticized for excluding Jews as a distinct underrepresented class.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The Academy has no rules for how to categorize whether a performance is leading or supporting, and it is up to the discretion of the studios whether a given performance is submitted for either Best Actor/Actress or Best Supporting Actor/Actress.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] This has led to situations where a film has two or more co-leads, and one of these is submitted in a supporting category to avoid the two leads competing against each other, and to increase the film's chances of winning.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] This practice has been derisively called "category fraud".
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] For example, Rooney Mara was nominated for Best Supporting Actress for *Carol* (2015), despite her having a comparable amount of screentime to Cate Blanchett, who was nominated for Best Actress.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Another example is *Once Upon a Time in Hollywood* (2019), where Brad Pitt was nominated for and won Best Supporting Actor, even though he played an equally important role to Best Actor nominee Leonardo DiCaprio.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] In both these cases, critics argued that the studios behind the films had placed someone who was actually a leading actor or actress into the supporting categories to avoid them competing against their co-lead.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Following its April 2019 board meeting, the Academy Board of Governors agreed to retain the current rules that allow for streaming media films to be eligible for Oscars as long as they have had limited theatrical runs.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] During the 94th Academy Awards on March 27, 2022, Chris Rock joked about Jada Pinkett Smith's shaved head with a *G.I.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Will Smith walked onstage and slapped Rock across the face, then returned to his seat and told Rock, twice, to "Keep my wife's name out [of] your fucking mouth!" While later accepting the Best Actor award for *King Richard*, Smith apologized to the Academy and the other nominees, but not to Rock.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Rock decided not to press charges against Smith.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] On April 8, 2022, the Academy made an announcement via a letter sent by president David Rubin and CEO Dawn Hudson informing the public that Will Smith had received a ten-year ban from attending the Oscars as a result of the incident.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Some winners critical of the Academy Awards have boycotted the ceremonies and refused to accept their Oscars.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The first to do so was screenwriter Dudley Nichols (Best Writing in 1935 for *The Informer*).
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Nichols boycotted the 8th Academy Awards ceremony because of conflicts between the Academy and the Writers' Guild.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Nichols eventually accepted the 1935 award three years later, at the 1938 ceremony.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Nichols was nominated for three further Academy Awards during his career.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Scott became the second person to refuse his award (Best Actor in 1970 for *Patton*) at the 43rd Academy Awards ceremony.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Scott described it as a "meat parade", saying, "I don't want any part of it".
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The third person to refuse the award was Marlon Brando, who refused his award (Best Actor for 1972's *The Godfather*), citing the film industry's discrimination against and mistreatment of Native Americans.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] At the 45th Academy Awards ceremony, Brando asked actress and civil rights activist Sacheen Littlefeather to read a 15-page speech in his place, detailing his criticisms, for which there was booing and cheering by the audience.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] In 2022, Littlefeather was accused by her sisters of misrepresenting her ancestry as Native American.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Adding to the controversy was that the award for Best Animated Short Film (the nominees for which were mostly made up of shorts not aimed at children) was one of the eight categories that were not presented during the live broadcast.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Alberto Mielgo, director of *The Windshield Wiper*, later gave an acceptance speech for the Oscar: "Animation is an art that includes every single art that you can imagine.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] I'm very honored because this is just the beginning of what we can do with animation." Some speculations suggested that the speech played a role in the decision not to broadcast the award.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The PG-13-rated *The Boy and the Heron* would subsequently win the award.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] It has become a tradition to give out gift bags to the presenters and performers at the Oscars.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] In recent years, these gifts have been extended to award nominees and winners.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The value of each of these gift bags can reach into the tens of thousands of dollars.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] In 2014, the value was reported to be as high as $80,000.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] The value has risen to the point where the U.S.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Internal Revenue Service issued a statement regarding the gifts and their taxable status.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Some of the gifts have even had a "risque" element to them; in 2014, the adult products retailer Adam & Eve had a "Secret Room Gifting Suite".
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] Celebrities visiting the gifting suite included Judith Hoag, Carolyn Hennesy, Kate Linder, Chris Mulkey, Jim O'Heir and John Salley.
[src:connecticut-college/academy-award-p02] From 2006 onwards, results are Live+SD; all previous years are live viewing.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Adelphi University began with the Adelphi Academy, founded in Brooklyn, New York, in 1863.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The academy was a private preparatory school located at 412 Adelphi Street, in the Fort Greene neighborhood of Brooklyn, but later moved to Clinton Hill.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1893, Charles Herbert Levermore was appointed as the head of Adelphi Academy.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Seeking to establish a liberal arts college for the City of Brooklyn, Levermore received a charter from the Board of Regents of the State of New York, officially establishing Adelphi College on June 24, 1896.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The college received its charter through the efforts of Timothy Woodruff, former Lieutenant Governor of New York and future first president of the board of trustees.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Adelphi was one of the first coeducational institutions to receive a charter from the State of New York.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] At the time of its foundation, the college numbered 57 students and 16 instructors.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The Adelphi Academy continued to exist as a separate but nonetheless connected entity to the college.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The new college was located in a building behind the Adelphi Academy, on the corner of St.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] James's Place and Clifton Place, in Brooklyn.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The building that originally housed Adelphi is now used by Pratt Institute for their School of Architecture.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1912, Adelphi became a women's college.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1922, the school raised over one million dollars to expand the overcrowded facilities in Brooklyn.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1925, Adelphi College severed its ties with the Adelphi Academy, the latter closing in 1930.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1929, the college moved from its founding location in Brooklyn to the current location of its main campus in Garden City, New York.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The original "academy" continues to function as a P–12 school in Brooklyn.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The original three buildings of the Garden City campus, Levermore Hall, Blodgett Hall and Woodruff Hall, were designed by McKim, Mead and White.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1938, the Dance Program was founded by Ruth St.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1943, the School of Nursing was established.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1946, after World War II ended, Adelphi reverted to a coeducational college.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1963, the New York State Board of Regents granted the college university status, and the name was changed to Adelphi University.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1964, the School of Business was founded.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1966, the Institute for Advanced Psychological Studies was founded.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1973, the university established ABLE (Adult Baccalaureate Learning Experience) for the education of adults.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1995, the Honors College was founded.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In January 1963, Adelphi Suffolk College (which had started out in 1955 offering extension courses in Suffolk County, New York) purchased the former W.K.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 1968, it was spun off to Dowling College after its chief benefactor, Robert Dowling.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Adelphi faced a serious scandal in 1996, as the school celebrated its 100th anniversary.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] University president Peter Diamandopoulos and the board of trustees were accused of neglect of duty, misconduct, and failure to carry out the educational purposes of Adelphi.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The New York State Board of Regents was called in to investigate; Diamandopoulos, along with all but one of the board of trustees, was dismissed from office.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Adelphi University also participates in the National Association of Independent Colleges and Universities's (NAICU) University and College Accountability Network (U-CAN).
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 2023, the Princeton Review ranked Adelphi University a "Green College" making the list of environmentally responsible colleges and universities across the country.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Adelphi is frequently listed amongst the U.S.' most liberal colleges.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In August 2023, Adelphi relocated the Manhattan Center location to Downtown Brooklyn at 179 Livingston Street.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Adelphi - Brooklyn Center, located on the 5th through 7th floors, is adjacent to Macy's Brooklyn store and shared with St.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In early 2026, Adelphi announced a new Manhattan Center at 529 Fifth Avenue in Midtown, a 51,000‑square‑foot facility housing graduate and professional programs in nursing, business, artificial intelligence, social work, and education.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Concurrently, the university launched a $55 million campus‑modernization project on its Garden City campus, funded in part by $125 million in tax‑exempt bonds.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In February 2026, a federal judge ruled that the university had erroneously found a student, Orion Newby, guilty of using artificial intelligence to write a paper, and ordered the plagiarism finding expunged.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The case was described by legal observers as “groundbreaking” for student due‑process rights in the age of AI‑detection software.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] During its 2026 Giving Day, the “1,896 Minutes to Give” campaign, Adelphi raised a record $2.25 million in support of students, with every sitting trustee participating.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The university's School of Social Work is home to the Adelphi New York Statewide Breast Cancer Hotline and Support Program The program began in 1980 as the Woman-to-Woman Hotline, a free and confidential service to help women with breast cancer.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] It is the second oldest breast cancer hotline in the United States; over 100 trained volunteers offer information and emotional support for people with breast cancer.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] There are professional social workers, bilingual Spanish-speaking staff and support staff, along with support groups, educational programs and individual counseling.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 2015, Adelphi University was ranked #17 in New York State by average professor salaries.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] News & World Report* rankings, Adelphi was tied for No.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] *Forbes* again ranked Adelphi the highest‑ranked private university on Long Island for the third consecutive year, and the Wall Street Journal recognized the university for social mobility and salary outcomes.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] 99 on its America’s Top Online Colleges 2026 list, and the university appeared in the *Times Higher Education* World University Rankings for the fourth consecutive year.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] On February 27, 2012, president Robert A.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Scott announced a gift of $9.5 million from Adelphi Board of Trustees Chairman Robert B.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The Adelphi University School of Business, established in 1964, was renamed the Robert B.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Willumstad School of Business in his honor.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Many of the buildings on the Garden City campus are symmetrical in nature.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] This is likely because garden cities are typically planned symmetrically.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] For example, Woodruff Hall has a second chimney solely to preserve the symmetry of the building.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Adelphi student activities include academic interests, cultural and language clubs, sports and recreation, religious / Interfaith Center, arts organizations, volunteer opportunities, fraternities, and sororities.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The Campus Pride Index awarded Adelphi five out of five stars for LGBTQ-friendly campuses.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The Adelphi Panthers are the athletic teams of Adelphi University.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] The Panthers compete at the NCAA Division II level for all sports and have been a member of the Northeast-10 Conference since 2009.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Since transitioning to the Northeast-10, the Adelphi Panthers have played in the East Region.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] In 2013, the Panthers were awarded the 2013 Northeast-10 Presidents' Cup, an honor awarded to the institution that compiles the most total points from all of its programs competing in league championships.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Notable faculty have included sex educator and Holocaust survivor Dr.
[src:connecticut-college/adelphi-university] Ruth, Pulitzer Prize-winning composer Paul Moravec, and US Labor Secretary Frances Perkins.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The college was founded in 1889 as **Decatur Female Seminary** by Presbyterian minister Frank Henry Gaines.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] In 1890, the name was changed to **Agnes Scott Institute** to honor the mother of the college's primary benefactor, Col.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The name was changed again to Agnes Scott College in 1906 and remains today a women's college.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott is considered the first higher education institution in the state of Georgia to receive regional accreditation.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The ninth and current president since July 2018 is Leocadia I.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Zak, who previously worked as director of the U.S.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] On July 27, 1994, the campus was listed on the National Register of Historic Places as part of the *South Candler Street-Agnes Scott College Historic District*.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The historic district boundaries are East College Ave., South McDonough St., S.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Candler St., East Hill St. and East Davis St.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] It includes the entire campus, as well as historic homes adjacent to the campus.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The campus is also designated by the City of Decatur as a historic district.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The Reverend Frank Henry Gaines served as the first President of Agnes Scott, formally known as Decatur Female Seminary School, for 27 years (1896–1923).
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] During his 27-year presidency, he ensured stability and success for the school, including the transition to the collegiate level, accreditation by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools, acquisition of 20 acres of land and 21 buildings and an increase in assets from $5,000 to $1.5 million.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott College is located within walking distance of downtown Decatur.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] It is served by Decatur station on the MARTA rail system, which is also a hub for buses, allowing students to travel to the greater Atlanta area.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott occupies more than 90 acres (360,000 m2) in Decatur.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The college also owns the Avery Glen apartments as well as more than a dozen houses in the surrounding neighborhoods housing faculty, staff, and students.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] There are also six dedicated undergraduate dormitories located on campus.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] American poet Robert Frost was first invited to speak at Agnes Scott in 1935, by English professor Emma May Laney, and he visited the college every winter from 1945 until his death in 1963.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] During his visits, he would read poetry in Presser Hall.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] A statue of the poet sculpted by George W.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] A collection of Robert Frost's poetry and letters can be viewed on the second floor of the McCain Library.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, named after Agnes Irvine Scott, is located at the center of "the main loop" and is a one among many Agnes Scott buildings that was listed in the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Main was built in 1891, making it the oldest building on campus.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] This is documented in the history of Agnes Scott by McNair titled *Lest We Forget* published in 1983.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] As technology became more advanced so did Main.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Main Hall was the first building on campus and in the neighborhood to have electric lighting.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Some say that people would gather outside of Main at night just to admire the light shining within the building.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1891, the Gazebo at Agnes Scott college has served a multitude of purposes throughout the years.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] It was originally located in front of Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, however in 1926 it was moved to the west end of Rebekah Scott Hall.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The gazebo has been used as an office, meeting room, meditation chapel, and the Day Student Hut.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1906, Rebekah Scott Hall is the second oldest building remaining at Agnes Scott College.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Rebekah Scott Hall cost $70,000 to build.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] It is named after George Washington Scott's wife, Rebekah Butcher Scott.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The first floor of Rebekah Scott Hall contains offices, the office of financial aid, and the office of admissions.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The second and third floors are used as student housing.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Inman Hall, known commonly as Inman Hall, was built in 1911 and is the oldest building at Agnes Scott College which is used exclusively for student housing.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] In 1985, Inman had major renovations and the third floor was converted into study spaces for students.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] It is made from Indiana limestone and is three stories high.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The building faces west and has a large veranda which stretches along the front of the building.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Jennie D, Inman Hall was gifted to Agnes Scott College by Samuel.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1923, the Anna Young Alumnae House is dedicated to former science professor and Agnes Scott alumnae, Anna Irwin Young.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Originally the Alumnae House was a central gathering place for ASC alumnae.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The house and bedrooms are now used as a campus guest house.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Behind the house is the Alumnae Garden which houses a statue honoring Robert Frost.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The Anna Young Alumnae House underwent renovations from 2005 until 2009, after which it was re-opened.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The Bradley Observatory at Agnes Scott houses the Beck Telescope, a 30-inch (760 mm) Cassegrain reflector, as well as a planetarium with 70-seat capacity and a radio telescope.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Recently Agnes Scott College and the Georgia Tech Research Institute have collaborated on a project that added a LIDAR facility to the observatory.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The college's science building, the Bullock Science Center, contains a three-story rendering of part of the nucleotide sequence from Agnes Scott's mitochondrial DNA.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The DNA came from a blood sample of an ASC alumna who is a direct descendant of the college's namesake.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott has committed to becoming a carbon-neutral institute by the college's 150th anniversary in 2039 and has taken steps such as partnering with the Clean Air Campaign to reduce its impact on the local environment.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] As of 2015, the college has five solar arrays, four of which are part of Georgia Power's Advanced Solar Initiative.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The fifth array is on the rooftop of the Bradley Observatory and is also used for student research.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The renovation of Campbell Hall into a mixed-use residence hall, learning center, and office space was concluded in 2014 and included installation of a hydro-geothermic HVAC system.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott offers 34 undergraduate majors and 9 graduate and post-baccalaureate programs.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The undergraduate core curriculum SUMMIT focuses on leadership development, global learning, and digital literacy.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] In 2019, Agnes Scott received the Heiskell Award for Scholars as Drivers of Innovation for its SUMMIT curriculum.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Undergraduate students are able to cross-register in other ARCHE member institutions.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The library at Agnes Scott College was an original Carnegie library built in 1910.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] A new library was authorized by the board of trustees in 1935 and opened in the fall of 1936.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] This new library was called the "Carnegie Library" and the original library was turned into a student center.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] It was renamed in 1951 for James McCain, on the occasion of his retirement as the 2nd President of the college.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] As of fall 2025, the student body consists of over 900 undergraduate and graduate students.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Approximately 60% of undergraduates that year were from Georgia.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Given Agnes Scott's emphasis on "mak[ing] lifelong friends, shar[ing] unforgettable experiences, discover[ing] meaningful places and find[ing] belonging in [their] community," a majority of students are encouraged to live on campus.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Thus, most students are expected to live in on-campus housing for all four years as an undergraduate at Agnes Scott College.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] However, the proportion of commuter students has increased (from 15.6 to 18.0 percent between the 2014–2015 and 2019–2020 academic year) due to limited housing caused from an increase in the student population (from 849 to 986 total students) and renovations to the residence halls.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] There are six resident halls situated around the Northern edge of the campus: Winship, Walters, Inman, Rebekah, Campbell, and Agnes Scott Hall (nicknamed "Main").
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] There are over 60 student organizations on campus.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The college hosts several student publications, including *The Silhouette*, the college's yearbook published annually, and *The Aurora*, Agnes Scott's literary magazine, and *The Profile*, Agnes Scott newspaper.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] All students are invited to join the staff.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott is a member of the National Collegiate Athletic Association Division III which fields six sports teams including basketball, cross country, soccer, softball, tennis, and volleyball.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] All teams compete in the Collegiate Conference of the South (CCS).
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott was named as one of the Colleges That Change Lives (CTCL).
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The campus has been a filming location for many productions, including the filming location for Windsor College in Scream 2, with its campus standing in for the fictional university where Sidney Prescott enrolls to escape her past.
[src:connecticut-college/agnes-scott-college] The college's Gothic architecture, particularly the main hall, provided the backdrop for many scenes, including the gazebo where a key reunion takes place.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] Marcucci played at the Episcopal Academy through high school.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] He also played as part of the Penn Fusion academy until 2017.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] In 2017, Marcucci attended Connecticut College to play college soccer.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] With the Camels, Marcucci appeared in 54 of the team's 55 matches between 2017 and 2019; the 2020 season was canceled due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] Marcucci finished his career with a school-record 25 career shutouts to go along with an .887 save percentage, and an 0.50 goals against average.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] Marcucci earned a place on the NCAA All-America First Team as the nation's top Division III goalkeeper twice by both the United Soccer Coaches and D3soccer.com in 2018 and 2019.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] He was also named the NESCAC Rookie of the Year in 2017 and the NESCAC Player of the Year in 2018.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] While at college, Marcucci also appeared for NPSL side West Chester United during their 2019 season.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] He was set to play with the team during their 2020 season in the USL League Two, but the season was eventually canceled.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] On January 21, 2021, Marcucci was selected 67th overall in the 2021 MLS SuperDraft by New York Red Bulls.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] He became the first ever draft pick from Connecticut College and was the first Division III pick since 2016.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] On April 15, 2021, Marcucci signed with New York's USL Championship side New York Red Bulls II.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] He made his debut on May 14, 2021, starting in a 1–0 loss to the Miami FC.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] On May 18, 2021, Marcucci recorded his first win with New York in a 2–1 victory over Loudoun United.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] On September 11, 2021, Marcucci moved to the New York Red Bulls first team roster in MLS.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] On July 21, 2024, Marcucci was loaned out to Finnish Veikkausliiga club IF Gnistan until the end of the 2024 season.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] He debuted with his new team in Veikkausliiga in the next day on July 22, saving a penalty in stoppage-time and securing his side a point in a 2–2 away draw against Inter Turku.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] During his loan stint, Marcucci made 14 appearances for Gnistan, keeping five clean sheets.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] During this period he helped guide the club through the relegation round and into the Conference League play-offs, where they reached the semifinals.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] At the conclusion of his loan period in Finland, Marcucci returned to New York for the 2025 season.
[src:connecticut-college/aj-marcucci] On March 22, 2025, he made his first team debut for New York, starting in a 2–1 victory over Toronto FC.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL was at one point the most recognized brand on the Web in the United States.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL once provided a dial-up Internet service to millions of Americans and pioneered instant messaging and chat rooms with AOL Instant Messenger (AIM).
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 1998, AOL purchased Netscape for US$4.2 billion.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] By 2000, AOL was providing internet service to over 20 million consumers, dominating the market of internet service providers (ISPs).
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 2001, at the height of its popularity, it purchased the media conglomerate Time Warner in the largest merger in US history.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL shrank rapidly thereafter, partly due to the decline of dial-up and rise of broadband.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL was spun off from Time Warner in 2009, with Tim Armstrong appointed the new CEO.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Under his leadership, the company invested in media brands and advertising technologies.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 2015, AOL was acquired by Verizon Communications for $4.4 billion, and was merged with Yahoo! the following year after the latter was also acquired by Verizon.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In May 2021, Verizon announced it would sell Verizon Media (and thus AOL) to private equity firm Apollo Global Management for $5 billion, and the sale was completed at the end of August.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In October 2025, Apollo reached a $1.5 billion deal to sell AOL to the Italian conglomerate Bending Spoons.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL began in 1983, as a short-lived venture called **Control Video Corporation** (**CVC**), founded by William von Meister.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Its sole product was an online service called GameLine for the Atari 2600 video game console, after von Meister's idea of buying music on demand was rejected by Warner Communications.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Subscribers bought a modem from the company for $49.95 and paid a one-time $15 setup fee.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] GameLine permitted subscribers to temporarily download games and keep track of high scores, at a cost of $1 per game.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The telephone disconnected and the downloaded game would remain in GameLine's Master Module, playable until the user turned off the console or downloaded another game.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In January 1983, Steve Case was hired as a marketing consultant for Control Video on the recommendation of his brother, investment banker Dan Case.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In May 1983, Jim Kimsey became a manufacturing consultant for Control Video, which was near bankruptcy.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Kimsey was brought in by his West Point friend Frank Caufield, an investor in the company.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In early 1985, von Meister left the company.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On May 24, 1985, **Quantum Computer Services**, an online services company, was founded by Kimsey from the remnants of Control Video, with Kimsey as chief executive officer and Marc Seriff as chief technology officer.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The technical team consisted of Seriff, Tom Ralston, Ray Heinrich, Steve Trus, Ken Huntsman, Janet Hunter, Dave Brown, Craig Dykstra, Doug Coward, and Mike Ficco.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 1987, Case was promoted again to executive vice-president.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Kimsey soon began to groom Case to take over the role of CEO, which he did when Kimsey retired in 1991.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Kimsey changed the company's strategy, and in 1985, launched a dedicated online service for Commodore 64 and 128 computers, originally called Quantum Link ("Q-Link" for short).
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The Quantum Link software was based on software licensed from PlayNet, Inc., which was founded in 1983 by Howard Goldberg and Dave Panzl.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The service was different from other online services as it used the computing power of the Commodore 64 and the Apple II rather than just a "dumb" terminal.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] It passed tokens back and forth and provided a fixed-price service tailored for home users.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In May 1988, Quantum and Apple launched AppleLink Personal Edition for Apple II and Macintosh computers.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In August 1988, Quantum launched PC Link, a service for IBM-compatible PCs developed in a joint venture with the Tandy Corporation.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] After the company parted ways with Apple in October 1989, Quantum changed the service's name to America Online.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Case promoted and sold AOL as the online service for people unfamiliar with computers, in contrast to CompuServe, which was well established in the technical community.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] From the beginning, AOL included online games in its mix of products; many classic and casual games were included in the original PlayNet software system.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In February 1991, AOL for IBM PC compatibles running MS-DOS was launched using a GeoWorks interface; it was followed a year later by AOL for Windows 3.0.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] This coincided with growth in pay-based online services, like Prodigy, CompuServe, and GEnie.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] During the early 1990s, the average subscription lasted for about 25 months and accounted for $350 in total revenue.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Advertisements invited modem owners to "Try America Online FREE", promising free software and trial membership.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL discontinued Q-Link and PC Link in late 1994.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In September 1993, AOL added Usenet access to its features.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] This is commonly referred to as the "Eternal September", as Usenet's cycle of new users was previously dominated by smaller numbers of college and university freshmen gaining access in September and taking a few weeks to acclimate.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] This also coincided with a new "carpet bombing" marketing campaign by CMO Jan Brandt to distribute as many free trial AOL trial disks as possible through nonconventional distribution partners.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] At one point, 50% of the CDs produced worldwide had an AOL logo.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL quickly surpassed GEnie, and by the mid-1990s, it passed Prodigy (which for several years allowed AOL advertising) and CompuServe.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In November 1994, AOL purchased Booklink for its web browser, to give its users web access.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 1996, AOL replaced Booklink with a browser based on Internet Explorer, reportedly in exchange for inclusion of AOL in Windows.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL purchased search engine WebCrawler in 1995, but sold it to Excite the following year; the deal made Excite the sole search and directory service on AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] After the deal closed in March 1997, AOL launched its own branded search engine, based on Excite, called NetFind.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL charged its users an hourly fee until December 1996, when the company changed to a flat monthly rate of $19.95.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] During this time, AOL connections were flooded with users trying to connect, and many canceled their accounts due to constant busy signals.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] A commercial was made featuring Steve Case telling people AOL was working day and night to fix the problem.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Within three years, AOL's user base grew to 10 million people.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 1995, AOL was headquartered at 8619 Westwood Center Drive in the Tysons Corner CDP in unincorporated Fairfax County, Virginia in the Washington, D.C. metropolitan area. near the Town of Vienna.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL was quickly running out of room in October 1996 for its network at the Fairfax County campus.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In mid-1996, AOL moved to 22000 AOL Way in Dulles, unincorporated Loudoun County, Virginia to provide room for future growth.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In a five-year landmark agreement with the most popular operating system, AOL was bundled with Windows software.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On March 31, 1996, the short-lived eWorld was purchased by AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 1997, about half of all US homes with Internet access had it through AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] During this time, AOL's content channels, under Jason Seiken, including News, Sports, and Entertainment, experienced their greatest growth as AOL become the dominant online service internationally with more than 34 million subscribers.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On August 7, 1996, AOL experienced a total outage starting at 1:00 AM PST that would last nineteen hours and took over six million people offline.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In February 1998, AOL acquired CompuServe Interactive Services (CIS) via WorldCom (later Verizon), which kept Compuware's networking business.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In November 1998, AOL announced it would acquire Netscape, best known for their web browser, in a major $4.2 billion deal.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Another large acquisition in December 1999 was that of MapQuest, for $1.1 billion.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In January 2000, as new broadband technologies were being rolled out around the New York City metropolitan area and elsewhere across the United States, AOL and Time Warner announced plans to merge, forming AOL Time Warner, Inc.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The terms of the deal called for AOL shareholders to own 55% of the new, combined company.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The new company was led by executives from AOL, SBI, and Time Warner.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Gerald Levin, who had served as CEO of Time Warner, was CEO of the new company.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Michael Kelly (from AOL) was the chief financial officer, Robert W.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Pittman (from AOL) and Dick Parsons (from Time Warner) served as co-chief operating officers.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 2002, Jonathan Miller became CEO of AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The following year, AOL Time Warner dropped the "AOL" from its name.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] It was the largest merger in history when completed with the combined value of the companies at $360 billion.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] This value fell sharply, to as low as $120 billion, as markets repriced AOL's valuation as a pure internet firm more modestly when combined with the traditional media and cable business.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] This status did not last long, and the company's value rose again within three months.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] By the end of that year, the tide had turned against "pure" internet companies, with many collapsing under falling stock prices, and even the strongest companies in the field losing up to 75% of their market value.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The decline continued through 2001, but even with the losses, AOL was among the internet giants that continued to outperform brick and mortar companies.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 2004, along with the launch of AOL 9.0 Optimized, AOL also made available the option of personalized greetings which would enable the user to hear his or her name while accessing basic functions and mail alerts, or while logging in or out.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 2005, AOL broadcast the Live 8 concert live over the Internet, and thousands of users downloaded clips of the concert over the following months.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In late 2005, AOL released AOL Safety & Security Center, a bundle of McAfee Antivirus, CA anti-spyware, and proprietary firewall and phishing protection software.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] News reports in late 2005 identified companies such as Yahoo!, Microsoft, and Google as candidates for turning AOL into a joint venture.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Those plans were abandoned when it was revealed on December 20, 2005, that Google would purchase a 5% share of AOL for $1 billion.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On April 3, 2006, AOL announced that it would retire the full name America Online.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The official name of the service became AOL, and the full name of the Time Warner subdivision became AOL LLC.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On June 8, 2006, AOL offered a new program called AOL Active Security Monitor, a diagnostic tool to monitor and rate PC security status, and recommended additional security software from AOL or Download.com.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Two months later, AOL released AOL Active Virus Shield, a free product developed by Kaspersky Lab, that did not require an AOL account, only an internet email address.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The ISP side of AOL UK was bought by Carphone Warehouse in October 2006 to take advantage of its 100,000 LLU customers, making Carphone Warehouse the largest LLU provider in the UK.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In August 2006, AOL announced that it would offer email accounts and software previously available only to its paying customers, provided that users accessed AOL or AOL.com through an access method not owned by AOL (otherwise known as "third party transit", "bring your own access" or "BYOA").
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The move was designed to reduce costs associated with the "walled garden" business model by reducing usage of AOL-owned access points and shifting members with high-speed internet access from client-based usage to the more lucrative advertising provider AOL.com.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The change from paid to free access was also designed to slow the rate at which members canceled their accounts and defected to Microsoft Hotmail, Yahoo! or other free email providers.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Also in August, AOL informed its US customers of an increase in the price of its dial-up access to $25.90.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The increase was part of an effort to migrate the service's remaining dial-up users to broadband, as the increased price was the same as that of its monthly DSL access.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] However, AOL subsequently began offering unlimited dial-up access for $9.95 a month.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On November 16, 2006, Randy Falco succeeded Jonathan Miller as CEO.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In December 2006, AOL closed its last remaining call center in the United States, "taking the America out of America Online," according to industry pundits.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Service centers based in India and the Philippines continue to provide customer support and technical assistance to subscribers.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On September 17, 2007, AOL announced the relocation of one of its corporate headquarters from Dulles, Virginia to New York City and the combination of its advertising units into a new subsidiary called Platform A.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] This action followed several advertising acquisitions, most notably Advertising.com, and highlighted the company's new focus on advertising-driven business models.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL management stressed that "significant operations" would remain in Dulles, which included the company's access services and modem banks.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In October 2007, AOL announced the relocation of its other headquarters from Loudoun County, Virginia to New York City, while continuing to operate its Virginia offices.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] As part of the move to New York and the restructuring of responsibilities at the Dulles headquarters complex after the Reston move, Falco announced on October 15, 2007, plans to lay off 2,000 employees worldwide by the end of 2007, beginning "immediately".
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The result was a layoff of approximately 40% of AOL's employees.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Most compensation packages associated with the October 2007 layoffs included a minimum of 120 days of severance pay, 60 of which were offered in lieu of the 60-day advance notice requirement by provisions of the 1988 federal WARN Act.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] By November 2007, AOL's customer base had been reduced to 10.1 million subscribers, slightly more than the number of subscribers of Comcast and AT&T Yahoo!.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] According to Falco, as of December 2007, the conversion rate of accounts from paid access to free access was more than 80%.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On January 3, 2008, AOL announced the closing of its Reston, Virginia, data center, which was sold to CRG West.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On February 6, Time Warner CEO Jeff Bewkes announced that Time Warner would divide AOL's internet-access and advertising businesses, with the possibility of later selling the internet-access division.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On March 13, 2008, AOL purchased the social networking site Bebo for $850 million (£417 million).
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On July 25, AOL announced that it was shuttering Xdrive, AOL Pictures and BlueString to save on costs and focus on its core advertising business.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On October 31, AOL Hometown (a web-hosting service for the websites of AOL customers) and the AOL Journal blog hosting service were eliminated.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On March 12, 2009, Tim Armstrong, formerly with Google, was named chairman and CEO of AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On May 28, Time Warner announced that it would position AOL as an independent company after Google's shares ceased at the end of the fiscal year.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On November 23, AOL unveiled a new brand identity with the wordmark "Aol." superimposed onto canvases created by commissioned artists.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The new identity, designed by Wolff Olins, was integrated with all of AOL's services on December 10, the date upon which AOL traded independently for the first time since the Time Warner merger on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On April 6, 2010, AOL announced plans to shutter or sell Bebo.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On June 16, the property was sold to Criterion Capital Partners for an undisclosed amount, believed to be approximately $10 million.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In December, AIM eliminated access to AOL chat rooms, noting a marked decline in usage in recent months.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Under Armstrong's leadership, AOL followed a new business direction marked by a series of acquisitions.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] It announced the acquisition of Patch Media, a network of community-specific news and information sites focused on towns and communities.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On September 28, 2010, at the San Francisco TechCrunch Disrupt Conference, AOL signed an agreement to acquire TechCrunch.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On December 12, 2010, AOL acquired about.me, a personal profile and identity platform, four days after the platform's public launch.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On January 31, 2011, AOL announced the acquisition of European video distribution network goviral.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In March 2011, AOL acquired *HuffPost* for $315 million.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Shortly after the acquisition was announced, *Huffington Post* co-founder Arianna Huffington replaced AOL content chief David Eun, assuming the role of president and editor-in-chief of the AOL Huffington Post Media Group.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On March 10, AOL announced that it would cut approximately 900 workers following the *HuffPost* acquisition.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On September 14, 2011, AOL formed a strategic ad-selling partnership with two of its largest competitors, Yahoo and Microsoft.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The three companies would begin selling inventory on each other's sites.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The strategy was designed to help the companies compete with Google and advertising networks.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On February 28, 2012, AOL partnered with PBS to launch MAKERS, a digital documentary series focusing on high-achieving women in industries perceived as male-dominated such as war, comedy, space, business, Hollywood and politics.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Subjects for MAKERS episodes have included Oprah Winfrey, Hillary Clinton, Sheryl Sandberg, Martha Stewart, Indra Nooyi, Lena Dunham and Ellen DeGeneres.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On March 15, 2012, AOL announced the acquisition of Hipster, a mobile photo-sharing app, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On April 9, 2012, AOL announced a deal to sell 800 patents to Microsoft for $1.056 billion.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The deal included a perpetual license for AOL to use the patents.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In April, AOL took several steps to expand its ability to generate revenue through online video advertising.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The company announced that it would offer gross rating point (GRP) guarantee for online video, mirroring the television-ratings system and guaranteeing audience delivery for online-video advertising campaigns bought across its properties.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] This announcement came just days before the Digital Content NewFront (DCNF) a two-week event held by AOL, Google, Hulu, Microsoft, Vevo and Yahoo to showcase the participating sites' digital video offerings.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The DCNF was conducted in advance of the traditional television upfronts in the hope of diverting more advertising money into the digital space.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On April 24, the company launched the AOL On network, a single website for its video output.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In February 2013, AOL reported its fourth quarter revenue of $599.5 million, its first growth in quarterly revenue in eight years.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In August 2013, Armstrong announced that Patch Media would scale back or sell hundreds of its local news sites.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Not long afterward, layoffs began, with up to 500 out of 1,100 positions initially impacted.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On January 15, 2014, Patch Media was spun off, and majority ownership was held by Hale Global.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] By the end of 2014, AOL controlled 0.74% of the global advertising market, well behind industry leader Google's 31.4%.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On January 23, 2014, AOL acquired Gravity, a software startup that tracked users' online behavior and tailored ads and content based on their interests, for $83 million.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The deal, which included approximately 40 Gravity employees and the company's personalization technology, was Armstrong's fourth-largest deal since taking command in 2009.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Later that year, AOL acquired Vidible, a company that developed technology to help websites run video content from other publishers, and help video publishers sell their content to these websites.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The deal, which was announced December 1, 2014, was reportedly worth roughly $50 million.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On July 16, 2014, AOL earned an Emmy nomination for the AOL original series *The Future Starts Here* in the News and Documentary category.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] This came days after AOL earned its first Primetime Emmy Award nomination and win for *Park Bench with Steve Buscemi* in the Outstanding Short Form Variety Series.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Created and hosted by Tiffany Shlain, the series focused on humans' relationship with technology and featured episodes such as "The Future of Our Species", "Why We Love Robots" and "A Case for Optimism".
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On May 12, 2015, Verizon announced plans to buy AOL for $50 per share in a deal valued at $4.4 billion.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The transaction was completed on June 23.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Armstrong, who continued to lead the firm following regulatory approval, called the deal the logical next step for AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] "If you look forward five years, you're going to be in a space where there are going to be massive, global-scale networks, and there's no better partner for us to go forward with than Verizon." he said.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] "It's really not about selling the company today.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Analyst David Bank said he thought the deal made sense for Verizon.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The deal will broaden Verizon's advertising sales platforms and increase its video production ability through websites such as *HuffPost*, TechCrunch, and Engadget.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] However, Craig Moffett said it was unlikely the deal would make a big difference to Verizon's bottom line.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL had about two million dial-up subscribers at the time of the buyout.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The announcement caused AOL's stock price to rise 17%, while Verizon's stock price dropped slightly.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Shortly before the Verizon purchase, on April 14, 2015, AOL launched ONE by AOL, a digital marketing programmatic platform that unifies buying channels and audience management platforms to track and optimize campaigns over multiple screens.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Later that year, on September 15, AOL expanded the product with ONE by AOL: Creative, which is geared towards creative and media agencies to similarly connect marketing and ad distribution efforts.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On May 8, 2015, AOL reported its first-quarter revenue of $625.1 million, $483.5 million of which came from advertising and related operations, marking a 7% increase from Q1 2014.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Over that year, the AOL Platforms division saw a 21% increase in revenue, but a drop in adjusted OIBDA due to increased investments in the company's video and programmatic platforms.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On June 29, 2015, AOL announced a deal with Microsoft to take over the majority of its digital advertising business.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Under the pact, as many as 1,200 Microsoft employees involved with the business will be transferred to AOL, and the company will take over the sale of display, video, and mobile ads on various Microsoft platforms in nine countries, including Brazil, Canada, the United States, and the United Kingdom.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Additionally, Google Search will be replaced on AOL properties with Bing—which will display advertising sold by Microsoft.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Both advertising deals are subject to affiliate marketing revenue sharing.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On September 3, 2015, AOL agreed to buy Millennial Media for $238 million.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On October 23, 2015, AOL completed the acquisition.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On October 1, 2015, Go90, a free ad-supported mobile video service aimed at young adult and teen viewers that Verizon owns and AOL oversees and operates, launched its content publicly after months of beta testing.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The initial launch line-up included content from Comedy Central, HuffPost, Nerdist News, Univision News, Vice, ESPN and MTV.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On April 20, 2016, AOL acquired virtual reality studio RYOT to bring immersive 360 degree video and VR content to HuffPost's global audience across desktop, mobile, and apps.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In July 2016, Verizon Communications announced its intent to purchase the core internet business of Yahoo!.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Verizon merged AOL with Yahoo into a new company called "Oath Inc.", which in January 2019 rebranded itself as Verizon Media.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In April 2018, Oath Inc. sold Moviefone to MoviePass Parent Helios and Matheson Analytics.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In November 2020 the *Huffington Post* was sold to BuzzFeed in a stock deal.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On May 3, 2021, Verizon announced it would sell 90 percent of its Verizon Media division to Apollo Global Management for $5 billion, becoming the second independent incarnation of Yahoo Inc.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 2025, AOL ended its dial-up internet service.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In October 2025, Bending Spoons acquired AOL in a deal valued at roughly $1.5 billion.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In a statement, Bending Spoons CEO Luca Ferrari cited AOL's 30 million active users as part of what made the property attractive.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The purchase was quietly completed in January 2026, Bending Spoons then laid off more than 100 AOL employees in February 2026.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL's web ecosystem operates primarily as a content aggregator and digital service portal.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The AOL homepage aggregates news, lifestyle, and entertainment content from major syndicated third-party media wires and partner networks.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In addition to mobile-optimized web experiences, AOL produces mobile applications for its remaining properties and standalone software utilities.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL Mail is AOL's proprietary email client.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] It provides fully integrated webmail services and direct links to news headlines on AOL content sites.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL Plans offers multiple online safety and assistance subscription bundles: identity theft protection, data security tools, and a general online technical assistance service.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] In 2017, a paid internet suite version called AOL Desktop Gold was released, available for $4.99 per month after a trial period.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] It replaced the previous free software tier.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On January 10, 2018, all versions of the original AOL Desktop were shut down so AOL could focus towards AOL Desktop Gold and AOL Shield.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Following the shutdown of AIM, AOL's original legacy chat rooms continued to be accessible through AOL Desktop Gold until the chat system was permanently shut down on December 15, 2020.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] When it owned the Huffington Post, AOL's content ecosystem featured contributors consisting of over 20,000 bloggers, including politicians, celebrities, academics, and policy experts, who contributed on a wide range of topics.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Several major media brands formerly owned by AOL—including Engadget, Autoblog, TechCrunch, and Built by Girls—became part of Verizon Media (now Yahoo) following Verizon's acquisition of AOL in 2015.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Mobile applications and experimental products associated with these eras, such as Alto, Pip, and Vivv, have also been retired.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL previously operated a global portfolio of advertising technologies and services.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] This included data and programmatic solutions handled through its proprietary ad technology stack, ONE by AOL, which was built on acquisitions such as AdapTV (2013), Convertro (2014), Precision Demand (2014), and Vidible (2014).
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] ONE by AOL operated under two separate banners: ONE by AOL for Publishers and ONE by AOL for Advertisers.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] On September 10, 2018, parent company Oath consolidated BrightRoll, One by AOL, and Yahoo Gemini into a unified ad-tech platform named Oath Ad Platforms, which was later rebranded as Yahoo!
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL originally built its user base on Dial-up Internet access.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] While the service retained 2.1 million subscribers in 2015, membership plummeted to a few thousand by 2021 as remaining premium users transitioned to software support packages.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL officially discontinued its legacy dial-up service on September 30, 2025.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) was AOL's flagship proprietary instant-messaging tool launched in 1997.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] At its peak, billions of messages were sent daily across AIM and associated AOL chat properties.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Over time, it lost significant market share to competitors like Google Chat, Facebook Messenger, and text messaging.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] It also included a integrated video-chat tool, AV by AIM.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] AOL discontinued the AIM service on December 15, 2017.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Subsequent iterations shifted back to supporting the 9.X version lines.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Version 9.8 replaced existing Internet Explorer engine dependencies with the CEF engine to mimic modern web-browsing frameworks like Google Chrome.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Version 11 introduced a complete software architecture rewrite while preserving the 9.8 legacy layout.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The freeware software stack was fully deprecated in 2017 in favor of the paid subscription iteration, AOL Desktop Gold.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] Separately, the company maintained the **AOL Toolbar**, a web browser toolbar distributed as a Mozilla plug-in offering immediate web hooks into fundamental AOL platforms.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p01] The toolbar utility was maintained from 2007 until its retirement in 2018.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In its earlier incarnation as a "walled garden" community and service provider, AOL received criticism for its community policies, terms of service, and customer service.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Prior to 2006, AOL was known for its direct mailing of CD-ROMs and 3.5-inch floppy disks containing its software.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The disks were distributed in large numbers; at one point, half of the CDs manufactured worldwide had AOL logos on them.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The marketing tactic was criticized for its environmental cost, and AOL CDs were recognized as *PC World*'s most annoying tech product.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL used a system of volunteers to moderate its chat rooms, forums and user communities.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The program dated back to AOL's early days, when it charged by the hour for access and one of its highest billing services was chat.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL provided free access to community leaders in exchange for moderating the chat rooms, and this effectively made chat very cheap to operate, and more lucrative than AOL's other services of the era.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] There were 33,000 community leaders in 1996.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] All community leaders received hours of training and underwent a probationary period.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] While most community leaders moderated chat rooms, some ran AOL communities and controlled their layout and design, with as much as 90% of AOL's content being created or overseen by community managers until 1996.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] By 1996, ISPs were beginning to charge flat rates for unlimited access, which they could do at a profit because they only provided internet access.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Even though AOL would lose money with such a pricing scheme, it was forced by market conditions to offer unlimited access in October 1996.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In order to return to profitability, AOL rapidly shifted its focus from content creation to advertising, resulting in less of a need to carefully moderate every forum and chat room to keep users willing to pay by the minute to remain connected.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] After unlimited access, AOL considered scrapping the program entirely, but continued it with a reduced number of community leaders, with scaled-back roles in creating content.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Although community leaders continued to receive free access, after 1996 they were motivated more by the prestige of the position and the access to moderator tools and restricted areas within AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] By 1999, there were over 15,000 volunteers in the program.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In May 1999, two former volunteers filed a class-action lawsuit alleging AOL violated the Fair Labor Standards Act by treating volunteers like employees.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Volunteers had to apply for the position, commit to working for at least three to four hours a week, fill out timecards and sign a non-disclosure agreement.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] On July 22, AOL ended its youth corps, which consisted of 350 underage community leaders.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] At this time, the United States Department of Labor began an investigation into the program, but it came to no conclusions about AOL's practices.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL ended its community leader program on June 8, 2005.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The class action lawsuit dragged on for years, even after AOL ended the program and AOL declined as a major internet company.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In 2010, AOL finally agreed to settle the lawsuit for $15 million.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The community leader program was described as an example of co-production in a 2009 article in *International Journal of Cultural Studies*.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL has faced a number of lawsuits over claims that it has been slow to stop billing customers after their accounts have been canceled, either by the company or the user.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In addition, AOL changed its method of calculating used minutes in response to a class action lawsuit.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Previously, AOL would add 15 seconds to the time a user was connected to the service and round up to the next whole minute (thus, a person who used the service for 12 minutes and 46 seconds would be charged for 14 minutes).
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL claimed this was to account for sign on/sign off time, but because this practice was not made known to its customers, the plaintiffs won (some also pointed out that signing on and off did not always take 15 seconds, especially when connecting via another ISP).
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL disclosed its connection-time calculation methods to all of its customers and credited them with extra free hours.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In addition, the AOL software would notify the user of exactly how long they were connected and how many minutes they were being charged.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL was sued by the Ohio Attorney General in October 2003 for improper billing practices.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL agreed to resolve any consumer complaints filed with the Ohio AG's office.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In December 2006, AOL agreed to provide restitution to Florida consumers to settle the case filed against them by the Florida Attorney General.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Many customers complained that AOL personnel ignored their demands to cancel service and stop billing.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In response to approximately 300 consumer complaints, the New York Attorney General's office began an inquiry of AOL's customer service policies.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The investigation revealed that the company had an elaborate scheme for rewarding employees who purported to retain or "save" subscribers who had called to cancel their Internet service.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In many instances, such retention was done against subscribers' wishes, or without their consent.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Under the scheme, customer service personnel received bonuses worth tens of thousands of dollars if they could successfully dissuade or "save" half of the people who called to cancel service.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] For several years, AOL had instituted minimum retention or "save" percentages, which consumer representatives were expected to meet.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] These bonuses, and the minimum "save" rates accompanying them, had the effect of employees not honoring cancellations, or otherwise making cancellation unduly difficult for consumers.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] On August 24, 2005, America Online agreed to pay $1.25 million to the state of New York and reformed its customer service procedures.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Under the agreement, AOL would no longer require its customer service representatives to meet a minimum quota for customer retention in order to receive a bonus.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] However the agreement only covered people in the state of New York.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] On June 13, 2006, Vincent Ferrari documented his account cancellation phone call in a blog post, stating he had switched to broadband years earlier.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In the recorded phone call, the AOL representative refused to cancel the account unless the 30-year-old Ferrari explained why AOL hours were still being recorded on it.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Ferrari insisted that AOL software was not even installed on the computer.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] When Ferrari demanded that the account be canceled regardless, the AOL representative asked to speak with Ferrari's father, for whom the account had been set up.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] When CNBC reporters tried to have an account on AOL cancelled, they were hung up on immediately and it ultimately took more than 45 minutes to cancel the account.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] On July 19, 2006, AOL's entire retention manual was released on the Internet.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] On August 3, 2006, Time Warner announced that the company would be dissolving AOL's retention centers due to its profits hinging on $1 billion in cost cuts.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The company estimated that it would lose more than six million subscribers over the following year.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Prior to 2006, AOL often sent unsolicited mass direct mail of 31⁄2" floppy disks and CD-ROMs containing their software.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] They were the most frequent user of this marketing tactic, and received criticism for the environmental cost of the campaign.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] According to *PC World*, in the 1990s "you couldn't open a magazine (*PC World* included) or your mailbox without an AOL disk falling out of it".
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The mass distribution of these disks was seen as wasteful by the public and led to protest groups.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] One such was No More AOL CDs, a web-based effort by two IT workers to collect one million disks with the intent to return the disks to AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The website was started in August 2001, and an estimated 410,176 CDs were collected by August 2007 when the project was shut down.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In 2000, AOL was served with an $8 billion lawsuit alleging that its AOL 5.0 software caused significant difficulties for users attempting to use third-party Internet service providers.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The lawsuit sought damages of up to $1000 for each user that had downloaded the software cited at the time of the lawsuit.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL later agreed to a settlement of $15 million, without admission of wrongdoing.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The AOL software then was given a feature called AOL Dialer, or AOL Connect on Mac OS X.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] This feature allowed users to connect to the ISP without running the full interface.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] This allowed users to use only the applications they wish to use, especially if they do not favor the AOL Browser.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL 9.0 was once identified by Stopbadware as being *under investigation* for installing additional software without disclosure, and modifying browser preferences, toolbars, and icons.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] However, as of the release of AOL 9.0 VR (Vista Ready) on January 26, 2007, it was no longer considered badware due to changes AOL made in the software.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] When AOL gave clients access to Usenet in 1993, they hid at least one newsgroup in standard list view: *alt.aol-sucks*.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL did list the newsgroup in the alternative description view, but changed the description to "Flames and complaints about America Online".
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] With AOL clients swarming Usenet newsgroups, the old, existing user base started to develop a strong distaste for both AOL and its clients, referring to the new state of affairs as Eternal September.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL discontinued access to Usenet on June 25, 2005.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] No official details were provided as to the cause of decommissioning Usenet access, except providing users the suggestion to access Usenet services from a third-party, Google Groups.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL then provided community-based message boards in lieu of Usenet.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL has a detailed set of guidelines and expectations for users on their service, known as the Terms of Service (TOS, also known as Conditions of Service (COS) in the UK).
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] It is separated into three different sections: *Member Agreement*, *Community Guidelines* and *Privacy Policy*.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] All three agreements are presented to users at time of registration and digital acceptance is achieved when they access the AOL service.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] During the period when volunteer chat room hosts and board monitors were used, chat room hosts were given a brief online training session and test on Terms of Service violations.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] There have been many complaints over rules that govern an AOL user's conduct.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Some users disagree with the TOS, citing the guidelines are too strict to follow coupled with the fact the TOS may change without users being made aware.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] A considerable cause for this was likely due to alleged censorship of user-generated content during the earlier years of growth for AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] This decision drew fire from MoveOn, which characterized the program as an "email tax", and the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF), which characterized it as a shakedown of non-profits.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] A website called Dearaol.com was launched, with an online petition and a blog that garnered hundreds of signatures from people and organizations expressing their opposition to AOL's use of Goodmail.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Esther Dyson defended the move in an editorial in *The New York Times*, saying "I hope Goodmail succeeds, and that it has lots of competition.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] I also think it and its competitors will eventually transform into services that more directly serve the interests of mail recipients.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Tim Lee of the Technology Liberation Front posted an article that questioned the Electronic Frontier Foundation's adopting a confrontational posture when dealing with private companies.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] SpamAssassin developer Justin Mason posted some criticism of the EFF's and Moveon's "going overboard" in their opposition to the scheme.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The dearaol.com campaign lost momentum and disappeared, with the last post to the now defunct dearaol.com blog—"AOL starts the shakedown" being made on May 9, 2006.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Comcast, who also used the service, announced on its website that Goodmail had ceased operations and as of February 4, 2011, they no longer used the service.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] On August 4, 2006, AOL released a compressed text file on one of its websites containing 20 million search keywords for over 650,000 users over a three-month period between March 1 and May 31, 2006, intended for research purposes.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL pulled the file from public access by August 7, but not before its wide distribution on the Internet by others.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Derivative research, titled *A Picture of Search*, was published by authors Pass, Chowdhury and Torgeson for The First International Conference on Scalable Information Systems.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The data were used by websites such as AOLstalker for entertainment purposes, where users of AOLstalker are encouraged to judge AOL clients based on the humorousness of personal details revealed by search behavior.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] In 2003, Jason Smathers, an AOL employee, was convicted of stealing America Online's 92 million screen names and selling them to a known spammer.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Smathers pled guilty to conspiracy charges in 2005.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Smathers pled guilty to violations of the US CAN-SPAM Act of 2003.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] He was sentenced in August 2005 to 15 months in prison; the sentencing judge also recommended Smathers be forced to pay $84,000 in restitution, triple the $28,000 that he sold the addresses for.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] On February 27, 2012, a class action lawsuit was filed against Support.com, Inc. and partner AOL, Inc.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] The companies then offered to sell software—for which AOL allegedly charged $4.99 a month and Support.com $29—to remedy those problems.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Both AOL, Inc. and Support.com, Inc. settled on May 30, 2013, for $8.5 million.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] This included $25.00 to each valid class member and $100,000 each to Consumer Watchdog and the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL continues to market Computer Checkup.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Following media reports about PRISM, NSA's massive electronic surveillance program, in June 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including AOL.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] According to leaks of said program, AOL joined the PRISM program in 2011.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] At one time, most AOL users had an online "profile" hosted by the AOL Hometown service.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] When AOL Hometown was discontinued, users had to create a new profile on Bebo.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] This was an unsuccessful attempt to create a social network that would compete with Facebook.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] When the value of Bebo decreased to a tiny fraction of the $850 million AOL paid for it, users were forced to recreate their profiles yet again, on a new service called AOL Lifestream.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] AOL decided to shut down Lifestream on February 24, 2017, and gave users one month's notice to save photos and videos that had been uploaded to Lifestream.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] Following the shutdown, AOL no longer provides any option for hosting user profiles.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] During the Hometown/Bebo/Lifestream era, another user's profile could be displayed by clicking the "Buddy Info" button in the AOL Desktop software.
[src:connecticut-college/aol-p02] After the shutdown of Lifestream, this was no longer supported, but opened to the AIM home page (www.aim.com), which also became defunct, redirecting to AOL's home page.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Conn is a four-year residential undergraduate institution with approximately 1,900 students.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Students choose courses from 41 programs, including interdisciplinary pathways and centers, with a majority choosing to study abroad.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The college is situated on a hill located adjacent to the Thames River.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] In 1982, Conn was inducted as a member of the New England Small College Athletic Conference (NESCAC), where its athletes compete as part of NCAA Division III.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Connecticut College was chartered in 1911 as Connecticut's only women's college, having been established as a direct response to Wesleyan University's decision to stop admitting women.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Wright and other Wesleyan alumnae convinced others to found this new college, espousing the increasing desire among women for higher education.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] To that end, the institution was initially chartered as Thames College, but a few months later the name was changed to the Connecticut College for Women.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Their initial endowment came from financial assistance from the city of New London and its residents, along with a number of wealthy benefactors.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The college sits on a former dairy farm owned by Charles P.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] He died in 1904 and his wife Harriet (Jerome) Alexander died in 1911.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Their son Frank sold a large part of the land to the trustees to found Connecticut College.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The *Hartford Daily Times* ran an article on October 12, 1935, marking the college's 20th anniversary: "On September 27, 1915, the college opened its doors to students.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The entering class was made up of 99 freshmen students, candidates for degrees, and 52 special students, a total registration of 151.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] A fine faculty of 23 members had been engaged and a library of 6,000 volumes had been gathered together." The college became co-educational in 1969, as President Charles E.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Shain claimed that there was evidence that women were becoming uninterested in attending women's colleges.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] At that time, the school adopted its current name, Connecticut College.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] In the spring of 2023, students, faculty, and staff began protesting against college president Katherine Bergeron, who had been president of the college for nearly a decade.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] On March 24, 2023, after a vote of no confidence by the faculty in early March, Bergeron announced her resignation.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] On June 30, 2023, her last day in office, the board of trustees awarded her the title of President Emerita.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] On July 1, 2023, Leslie Wong began work as interim president of the college.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Andrea Chapdelaine, then-president of Hood College, was selected by the search committee to be the College's 12th president.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Her term officially began on June 1, 2024.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Chapdelaine was inaugurated on April 26, 2025.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The vast majority of the university property is in New London.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The main campus has three residential areas.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The North Campus contains the newest residential halls.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The South Campus contains residence halls along the west side of Tempel Green, across from several academic buildings.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The oldest dorms on campus are Plant House and Blackstone House, which were founded in 1914.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The campus houses the Winslow Ames House.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Connecticut College's two principal libraries are the Charles E.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Shain Library and the Greer Music Library, which is located in the Cummings Arts Center.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The Shain Library houses a collection of more than 500,000 books and periodicals and an extensive collection of electronic resources.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] It is also home to The Linda Lear Center for Special Collections and Archives, and to the Charles Chu Asian Art Reading Room.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The Lear Center has more than fifty book, manuscript, and art collections including research archives devoted to Rachel Carson, Eugene O'Neill, and Beatrix Potter.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The Charles Chu Asian Art Reading Room serves both as a quiet reading area and as the permanent exhibition space for the Chu-Griffis Art Collection.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The student center is "The College Center at Crozier-Williams" (often shortened to "Cro"), and is located in the middle of the campus.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The student center houses the Connecticut College bookstore (which doubles as a small convenience store), the campus post office, the Oasis Snack Shop, and the campus bar, Humphrey's (formerly The Cro Bar).
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] There are also student services offices as well as faculty offices and performance spaces for the Dance department.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Shain Library was originally dedicated in 1976 and is named after former College President Charles Shain.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] It was renovated, expanded, and re-dedicated in 2015.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The renovation was honored by the American Institute of Architects with a 2015 New England Honor Award in the category of Preservation.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] In 2016, LibraryJournal named the library a New Landmark Libraries Winner.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Performance spaces on campus include: Palmer Auditorium, Tansill Theater, housed in Hillyer Hall; Myers Dance Studio, housed in Crozier-Williams College Center; Harkness Chapel; and Evans Music Hall, Fortune Recital Hall, and Oliva Hall, all located in Cummings Art Center.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The campus makes up part of the Connecticut College Arboretum.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] This arboretum and botanical garden is free and open to the public year-round.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Harkness Chapel was designed by architect James Gamble Rogers, exhibiting his Colonial Georgian style, with twelve stained glass windows by G.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The building is used for denominational religious services, as well as for ceremonies, concerts and recitals, weddings, and other public functions.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The Lyman Allyn Art Museum is also located on campus, and while some classes are taught there, it is not part of the College itself.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The museum's website states that "the permanent collection includes over 10,000 paintings, sculpture, drawings, prints, furniture, and decorative arts, with an emphasis on American art from the 18th through 20th centuries." The collection is housed in a neo-classical building designed by Charles A.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Connecticut College is accredited by the New England Commission of Higher Education; it has been so continuously by NECHE or its predecessor since December 1932.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The college's academics are organized into thirty-one academic departments and seven interdisciplinary programs with forty-one traditional majors plus opportunities for self-designed courses of study.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Starting with the class of 2020, students at Connecticut College participate in a new interdisciplinary general education curriculum called Connections.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Its most popular majors, by 2024 graduates, were: Psychology (55), Economics (44), Computer Science (32), Government (29), and Biological Sciences (26).
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Connecticut College has a history of undergraduate research work and students are encouraged to make conference presentations and publish their work under the guidance of a professor.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The college had 187 full-time faculty members in 2024-25; 96% held a doctorate or other terminal degree.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The student-faculty ratio is about 9.4 to 1.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Admission to the college is considered "more selective" by *U.S.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The college received 7,950 applications for the Class of 2028 of which 2,945 (36%) were accepted.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Of the students in the entering class who submitted SAT scores, the middle 50% range was 690-755 for evidence-based reading and writing, and 660-740 for Math.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] News & World Report*, Connecticut College ranked 55th (tie) among national liberal arts colleges, 35th (tie) for "Best Undergraduate Teaching", 38th (tie) for "Most Innovative", 82nd for "Best Value", and 88th (tie) for "Top Performers in Social Mobility".
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Students live under the college's student-adjudicated honor code which was introduced in 1922.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Manifestations of the code include self-scheduled, non-proctored final exams.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] In a typical year, the college enrolls around 2000 men and women from 40 to 45 states, Washington, D.C., and 70 countries.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Approximately forty percent of students are men.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The fall 2024 student body was 68% White, 12% Hispanic, 3% Asian American, 5% African American, and 4% multiracial, with an additional 6% international students.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Connecticut College is a member of Phi Beta Kappa, the Annapolis Group, and the New England Small College Athletic Conference (NESCAC).
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Connecticut College does not offer a Greek system of fraternities or sororities.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The college has seven *a cappella* groups.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Women's groups are The ConnChords, The Shwiffs, and Miss Connduct.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The coeducational groups include the ConnArtists, Vox Cameli, and the Williams Street Mix.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Composer and violinist Margaret Jones Wiles founded and conducted the Connecticut College Orchestra when she taught at the college during the 1950s.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The college radio station (WCNI 90.9 FM) broadcasts a variety of music, including polka, blues, and Celtic music shows.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] A 2,000 watt transmitter installed in 2003 reaches much of the lower New England region.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Connecticut College has two student newspapers in which students handle all aspects of production: reporting, editing, ad sales, management, photography, layout, multimedia, and design.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] *The College Voice* is an editorially independent print and online bi-weekly publication, and *The Conntrarian* is an online opinion publication and a member of the Collegiate Network.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The Student Activities Council (SAC) runs events including club fairs, school dances, concerts, and off-campus excursions.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] SAC is also responsible for Floralia, the annual spring concert.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Recent Floralia artists have included Misterwives, Cash Cash, RAC, and St.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Unity House is the college's multicultural center which promotes, supports, educates, and implements multicultural awareness programs on campus.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] It supports various affinity, activist, and performance student groups.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The Feminist Resource, Education, & Empowerment (F.R.E.E) Center (formerly the Women's Center) provides a space for programming and events concerning gender issues.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The LGBTQIA Resource Center serves queer students and their allies by providing a supportive space, resource library, social events, and educational programming.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] It also hosts several student organizations.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] In August 2013, Campus Pride named Connecticut College one of the top 25 LGBT-friendly colleges and universities.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The College's teams participate as a member of the National Collegiate Athletic Association's Division III in the New England Small College Athletic Conference (NESCAC).
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] There are a total of 28 varsity athletics teams at Conn.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The twelve men's sports include basketball, cross country, ice hockey, lacrosse, rowing, soccer, squash, swimming and diving, tennis, track and field, and water polo.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The fifteen women's sports consist of basketball, cross country, field hockey, ice hockey, lacrosse, rowing, sailing, soccer, squash, swimming and diving, tennis, track and field, volleyball, and water polo.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] In 2014, the women's soccer team won the College's first NESCAC Championship, defeating Williams College in penalty kicks.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The team advanced to the NCAA Division III Tournament, but lost in the second round to Montclair State University in extra time.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] On December 4, 2021, the men's soccer team won the College's first-ever NCAA Division III National Championship by defeating Amherst College in penalty kicks.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Earlier in the season, the team won its first NESCAC regular season title.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] On January 21, 2021, Connecticut College goalkeeper AJ Marcucci was selected 67th overall in the 2021 MLS SuperDraft by New York Red Bulls.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] He became the first-ever draft pick from Connecticut College and was the first Division III pick since 2016.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The Connecticut College Women's Water Polo Team has won four Collegiate Water Polo Association Division III championships.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] Connecticut College has produced 427 collegiate All-Americans, sixty Academic All-Americans and twelve Olympic qualifiers.
[src:connecticut-college/connecticut-college] The Connecticut College Athletics Hall of Fame was established in 1989 and currently has over 100 inductees.
